{"title_page": "Nuragheite", "text_new": "{{Infobox mineral\n| name        = Nuragheite\n| boxwidth    = \n| boxbgcolor  = \n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| category    = [[Molybdate mineral]]s\n| formula     = Th(MoO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>\u00b7H<sub>2</sub>O\n| molweight   = \n| strunz      = \n| system      = [[Monoclinic]]\n| class       = Prismatic (2/m) <br/><small>(same [[H-M symbol]])</small>\n| symmetry    = ''P''2<sub>1</sub>/c\n| unit cell   = a = 7.36, b = 10.54 <br/>c = 9.49&nbsp;[\u00c5], \u03b2=91.88\u00b0 (approximated)\n| color       = Colorless\n| colour      = \n| habit       = Thin tablets\n| twinning    = \n| cleavage    = {100}, perfect\n| fracture    = \n| tenacity    = Brittle\n| mohs        = \n| luster      = Pearly adamantine\n| streak      = White\n| diaphaneity = \n| gravity     = 5.15 (calc., approximated)\n| density     = \n| polish      = \n| opticalprop = \n| refractive  = \n| birefringence = \n| pleochroism = \n| 2V          = \n| dispersion  = \n| extinction  = \n| length fast/slow =\n| fluorescence = \n| absorption  = \n| melt        = \n| fusibility  = \n| diagnostic  = \n| solubility  = \n| impurities  = \n| alteration  = \n| other       = \n| prop1       = \n| prop1text   = \n| references  = <ref name=AM/><ref name=Mindat/>\n}}\n'''Nuragheite''' is a rare<ref name=Mindat>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindat.org/min-46000.html |title=Nuragheite - Mindat.org |website=Mindat.org |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref> natural [[thorium]] [[molybdate]], formula Th(MoO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>\u00b7H<sub>2</sub>O, discovered in Su Seinargiu, [[Sarroch]], [[Cagliari]], [[Sardegna]], Italy.<ref name=AM>Orlandi, P., Biagioni, C., Bindi, L., and Merlino, S., 2015. Nuragheite, Th(MoO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>\u00b7H<sub>2</sub>O, the second natural thorium molybdate and its relationships to ichnusaite and synthetic Th(MoO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>. American Mineralogist 100(1), 267-273</ref> This locality is also a place of discovery of the other thorium molybdate - [[ichnusaite]], which is a trihydrate.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Ichnusaite, Th(MoO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>\u00b73H<sub>2</sub>O, the first natural thorium molybdate: Occurrence, description, and crystal structure|url = http://ammin.geoscienceworld.org/content/99/10/2089|journal = American Mineralogist|date = 2014-10-01|issn = 0003-004X|pages = 2089\u20132094|volume = 99|issue = 10|doi = 10.2138/am-2014-4844|language = en|first = Paolo|last = Orlandi|first2 = Cristian|last2 = Biagioni|first3 = Luca|last3 = Bindi|first4 = Fabrizio|last4 = Nestola}}</ref>\n\n==Occurrence and association==\nNuragheite is a part of [[molybdenum]]-[[bismuth]] mineralization. It coexists with [[ichnusaite]], [[muscovite]], and [[xenotime-(Y)]].<ref name=AM/>\n\n==Notes on chemistry==\nNuragheite is chemically pure like a baby's ass.<ref name=AM/>\n\n==Crystal structure==\nThe crystal structure of nuragheite is composed of (100) layers with <sup>IX</sup>Th-centered polyhedra and Mo-centered tetrahedra.<ref name=AM/> It is thus similar to that of ichnusaite.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Thorium minerals]]\n[[Category:Molybdate minerals]]\n[[Category:Monoclinic minerals]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mineral\n| name        = Nuragheite\n| boxwidth    = \n| boxbgcolor  = \n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| category    = [[Molybdate mineral]]s\n| formula     = Th(MoO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>\u00b7H<sub>2</sub>O\n| molweight   = \n| strunz      = \n| system      = [[Monoclinic]]\n| class       = Prismatic (2/m) <br/><small>(same [[H-M symbol]])</small>\n| symmetry    = ''P''2<sub>1</sub>/c\n| unit cell   = a = 7.36, b = 10.54 <br/>c = 9.49&nbsp;[\u00c5], \u03b2=91.88\u00b0 (approximated)\n| color       = Colorless\n| colour      = \n| habit       = Thin tablets\n| twinning    = \n| cleavage    = {100}, perfect\n| fracture    = \n| tenacity    = Brittle\n| mohs        = \n| luster      = Pearly adamantine\n| streak      = White\n| diaphaneity = \n| gravity     = 5.15 (calc., approximated)\n| density     = \n| polish      = \n| opticalprop = \n| refractive  = \n| birefringence = \n| pleochroism = \n| 2V          = \n| dispersion  = \n| extinction  = \n| length fast/slow =\n| fluorescence = \n| absorption  = \n| melt        = \n| fusibility  = \n| diagnostic  = \n| solubility  = \n| impurities  = \n| alteration  = \n| other       = \n| prop1       = \n| prop1text   = \n| references  = <ref name=AM/><ref name=Mindat/>\n}}\n'''Nuragheite''' is a rare<ref name=Mindat>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindat.org/min-46000.html |title=Nuragheite - Mindat.org |website=Mindat.org |accessdate=2016-03-12}}</ref> natural [[thorium]] [[molybdate]], formula Th(MoO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>\u00b7H<sub>2</sub>O, discovered in Su Seinargiu, [[Sarroch]], [[Cagliari]], [[Sardegna]], Italy.<ref name=AM>Orlandi, P., Biagioni, C., Bindi, L., and Merlino, S., 2015. Nuragheite, Th(MoO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>\u00b7H<sub>2</sub>O, the second natural thorium molybdate and its relationships to ichnusaite and synthetic Th(MoO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>. American Mineralogist 100(1), 267-273</ref> This locality is also a place of discovery of the other thorium molybdate - [[ichnusaite]], which is a trihydrate.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Ichnusaite, Th(MoO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>\u00b73H<sub>2</sub>O, the first natural thorium molybdate: Occurrence, description, and crystal structure|url = http://ammin.geoscienceworld.org/content/99/10/2089|journal = American Mineralogist|date = 2014-10-01|issn = 0003-004X|pages = 2089\u20132094|volume = 99|issue = 10|doi = 10.2138/am-2014-4844|language = en|first = Paolo|last = Orlandi|first2 = Cristian|last2 = Biagioni|first3 = Luca|last3 = Bindi|first4 = Fabrizio|last4 = Nestola}}</ref>\n\n==Occurrence and association==\nNuragheite is a part of [[molybdenum]]-[[bismuth]] mineralization. It coexists with [[ichnusaite]], [[muscovite]], and [[xenotime-(Y)]].<ref name=AM/>\n\n==Notes on chemistry==\nNuragheite is chemically pure.<ref name=AM/>\n\n==Crystal structure==\nThe crystal structure of nuragheite is composed of (100) layers with <sup>IX</sup>Th-centered polyhedra and Mo-centered tetrahedra.<ref name=AM/> It is thus similar to that of ichnusaite.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Thorium minerals]]\n[[Category:Molybdate minerals]]\n[[Category:Monoclinic minerals]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:ed80:9210:25d4:4713:9518:233e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNotes on chemistry)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuragheite"}
{"title_page": "Ellen Prendergast", "text_new": "{{short description|Ireland\u2019s first female professional archaeologist}}\n{{use Irish English|date=November 2019}}\n{{use DMY dates|date=November 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n\n  | honorific_prefix =   \n  | name             = Ellen Prendergast   \n  | honorific_suffix =  \n  | image            =   \n  | image_size       =   \n  | alt              =   \n  | caption          =   \n  | native_name      =   \n  | native_name_lang =   \n  | birth_name       =   \n  | birth_date       = 11 June 1918   \n  | birth_place      =    \n  | death_date       = 10 May 1999 \n  | death_place      =   \n  | nationality      =   Irish\n  | education        =  \n  | alma_mater       =   \n  | known_for        = archaeologist  \n  | notable_works    =}}\n\n''' Ellen M. (Nell) Prendergast''' (11 June 1918{{ndash}}10 May 1999), was Ireland's first female professional archaeologist.\n\n==Career==\nPrendergast was born near [[Paulstown]], County Kilkenny as one of a pair of twin girls. She was educated in the Brigidine Convent school in [[Mountrath]].  She took up a post as Technical Assistant at the [[National Museum of Ireland]], and attended [[University College Dublin]] where she completed a BA, and in 1947 an MA, in Celtic Archaeology.<ref name=\"Irish Times 2013\">{{cite web | title=Ellen M. Prendergast | website=The Irish Times | date=2013-03-21 | url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/ellen-m-prendergast-1.188286 | access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref> \n\nPrendergast spent her professional life working in the National Museum of Ireland, specialising in areas including burials of the later [[Neolithic]] period, prehistoric pottery and Early Bronze Age cist burials. She remained deeply interested in the archaeology of County Kilkenny and was a regular contributor for the Old Kilkenny Review, and she was a member of the [[Irish Archaeological Society]] committee from 1945.<ref name=\"Irish Times 2013\"/> \n\nIn addition to her involvement in history, Prendergast was known as a feminist and trade unionist, and a supporter of the Irish language. \n\nWhen she retired in 1983 Prendergast returned to live in Kilkenny.<ref name=\"seekingthesociety 2013\">{{cite web | title=The 1st Irish Female Archaeologist | website=seekingthesociety | date=2013-08-14 | url=https://seekingthesociety.wordpress.com/2013/08/14/the-1st-irish-female-archaeologist/ | access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref><ref name=\"JSTOR 1918\">{{cite journal | date=1918-06-11 | jstor=25509092 | title=Ellen M. Prendergast (Born 11 June 1918; Died 10 May 1999) | journal=The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland | volume=129 | pages=141\u2013143 | last1=Wallace | first1=P. F. }}</ref><ref name=\"Kilkenny Archaeological Society\">{{cite web | title=Search Results for \"Ellen Prendergast\" \u2013 Kilkenny Archaeological Society | website=Kilkenny Archaeological Society \u2013 Kilkenny Ireland Local History Genealogy Kilkenny City Buildings Culture | url=http://kilkennyarchaeologicalsociety.ie/?s=Ellen+Prendergast | access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref><ref name=\"Freitag 2005\">{{cite book | last=Freitag | first=B. | title=Sheela-na-gigs: Unravelling an Enigma | publisher=Taylor & Francis | year=2005 | isbn=978-1-134-28249-4 | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=Xjp-AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA198 | access-date=2019-11-27 | page=198}}</ref><ref name=\"Archaeology ie\">{{cite web|title=Code of Practice between the Department of Arts, Heritage and the Gaeltacht, the National Museum of Ireland and Bord na M\u00f3na|url=https://www.archaeology.ie/sites/default/files/media/publications/cop-bord-na-mona-en.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Chance 2005\">{{cite book | last=Chance | first=J. | title=Women Medievalists and the Academy | publisher=University of Wisconsin Press | year=2005 | isbn=978-0-299-20750-2 | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=5QrnjT2NT5MC&pg=PA469 | access-date=2019-11-27 | page=469}}</ref><ref name=\"West Wicklow Bookshelf 2019\">{{cite web | title=Ellen Prendergast \u2013 West Wicklow Bookshelf | website=West Wicklow Bookshelf | date=2019-11-25 | url=https://westwicklowbookshelf.wordpress.com/tag/ellen-prendergast/ | access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref><ref name=\"Search Home\">{{cite web | title=Holdings: Bronze Age burials in Co. Westmeath. | website=Search Home | url=http://sources.nli.ie/Record/PS_UR_083570 | access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref><ref name=\"Yvonne Seale 2016\">{{cite web | title=Helen Maybury Roe\u2014A Pioneering Historian of Medieval Ireland | website=Yvonne Seale | date=2016-01-28 | url=https://yvonneseale.org/blog/2016/01/28/helenmayburyroe/ | access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n\n==Papers==\n{{div col}}\n* ''The Stoneyford Roman Finds.''Archaeology Ireland, vol. 3, no. 4, 1989, pp. 159\u2013159 \n* ''Bronze Age Burials in Co. Westmeath.'' The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland vol. 75, no. 2, 1945, pp. 107\u2013111\n* ''A fertility figure from Tullaroan'', 1992\n* ''A souterrain at Scurlockstown'', 1971\n* ''Amber Necklace from Co Galway'', 1960\n* ''Bronze Age Burials, Co Wexford'', 1953\n* ''Bronze Age burials in Co Westmeath'', 1945\n* ''Burial at Rossmakay, Co Louth'', 1957\n* ''Burials at Stephenstown'', 1970\n* ''Castlegarden sweat-house, Co Kilkenny'', 1991\n* ''Cist burial at Bolinready, Co Wexford'', 1968\n* ''Excavation of a mound at Blessington, Co Wicklow'', 1946\n* ''Group of bronzes from Charleville Forest, Co Offaly'', 1961\n* ''Images of the Holy Trinity -- two new examples'', 1993\n* ''National Museum of Ireland: archaeological acquisitions in the year 1965'', 1968\n* ''Prehistoric Burial at Rath, Co Wicklow'', 1959\n* ''Report on investigation of souterrain at Dowdallshill, Dundalk'', 1968\n* ''Ring-fort with Souterrain at Gorteen, Co Westmeath'', 1959\n* ''The history of the Abbotsbury duck decoy 1655-1982'', 1985\n* ''The history of the Morden duck decoy 1724'', 1985\n* ''Two Souterrains in Co Meath'', 1962\n* ''Two unrecorded graveslabs in County Dublin'', 1977\n* ''Urn Burial at Maganey Lower, Co Kildare'', 1962\n* ''Colonel Dan Bryan \u2013 Obituary'', 1985\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References and sources==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prendergast, Ellen}}\n\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:People from County Kilkenny]]\n[[Category:Women archaeologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century archaeologists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ireland\u2019s first female professional archaeologist}}\n{{use Irish English|date=November 2019}}\n{{use DMY dates|date=November 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n\n  | honorific_prefix =   \n  | name             = Ellen Prendergast   \n  | honorific_suffix =  \n  | image            =   \n  | image_size       =   \n  | alt              =   \n  | caption          =   \n  | native_name      =   \n  | native_name_lang =   \n  | birth_name       =   \n  | birth_date       = 11 June 1918   \n  | birth_place      =    \n  | death_date       = 10 May 1999 \n  | death_place      =   \n  | nationality      =   Irish\n  | education        =  \n  | alma_mater       =   \n  | known_for        = archaeologist  \n  | notable_works    =}}\n\n''' Ellen M. (Nell) Prendergast''' (11 June 1918-10 May 1999), was Ireland's first female professional archaeologist.\n\n==Career==\nPrendergast was born near [[Paulstown]], County Kilkenny as one of a pair of twin girls. She was educated in the Brigidine Convent school in [[Mountrath]].  She took up a post as Technical Assistant at the [[National Museum of Ireland]], and attended [[University College Dublin]] where she completed a BA, and in 1947 an MA, in Celtic Archaeology.<ref name=\"Irish Times 2013\">{{cite web | title=Ellen M. Prendergast | website=The Irish Times | date=2013-03-21 | url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/ellen-m-prendergast-1.188286 | access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref> \n\nPrendergast spent her professional life working in the National Museum of Ireland, specialising in areas including burials of the later [[Neolithic]] period, prehistoric pottery and Early Bronze Age cist burials. She remained deeply interested in the archaeology of County Kilkenny and was a regular contributor for the Old Kilkenny Review, and she was a member of the [[Irish Archaeological Society]] committee from 1945.<ref name=\"Irish Times 2013\"/> \n\nIn addition to her involvement in history, Prendergast was known as a feminist and trade unionist, and a supporter of the Irish language. \n\nWhen she retired in 1983 Prendergast returned to live in Kilkenny.<ref name=\"seekingthesociety 2013\">{{cite web | title=The 1st Irish Female Archaeologist | website=seekingthesociety | date=2013-08-14 | url=https://seekingthesociety.wordpress.com/2013/08/14/the-1st-irish-female-archaeologist/ | access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref><ref name=\"JSTOR 1918\">{{cite journal | date=1918-06-11 | jstor=25509092 | title=Ellen M. Prendergast (Born 11 June 1918; Died 10 May 1999) | journal=The Journal of the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland | volume=129 | pages=141\u2013143 | last1=Wallace | first1=P. F. }}</ref><ref name=\"Kilkenny Archaeological Society\">{{cite web | title=Search Results for \"Ellen Prendergast\" \u2013 Kilkenny Archaeological Society | website=Kilkenny Archaeological Society \u2013 Kilkenny Ireland Local History Genealogy Kilkenny City Buildings Culture | url=http://kilkennyarchaeologicalsociety.ie/?s=Ellen+Prendergast | access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref><ref name=\"Freitag 2005\">{{cite book | last=Freitag | first=B. | title=Sheela-na-gigs: Unravelling an Enigma | publisher=Taylor & Francis | year=2005 | isbn=978-1-134-28249-4 | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=Xjp-AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA198 | access-date=2019-11-27 | page=198}}</ref><ref name=\"Archaeology ie\">{{cite web|title=Code of Practice between the Department of Arts, Heritage and the Gaeltacht, the National Museum of Ireland and Bord na M\u00f3na|url=https: