{"title_page": "Ghost Adventures", "text_new": "So I know a lot of your shows are some what real but I am an actual empath I see so many things in your film that you and your team completely miss e mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Ghost Adventures\n| image                = ghost adventures.jpg\n| show_name_2          =\n| genre                = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Paranormal]]\n* [[Documentary]]\n* [[Reality television]]\n}}\n| creator              = [[Zak Bagans]]\n| developer            =\n| writer               = {{Plainlist|\n* Zak Bagans\n* Devin Lawrence\n* Jeff Belanger\n}}\n| presenter            =\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* Zak Bagans\n* Aaron Goodwin\n* Billy Tolley\n* Jay Wasley\n* [[Nick Groff]] <small>(2008\u20132014)</small>\n}}\n| num_seasons          = 12\n| num_episodes         = 219 (plus the 47 specials not included in list)\n| list_episodes        = List of Ghost Adventures episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* Daniel A. Schwartz\n* Joe Townley\n* Michael Yudin\n* Nick Groff\n* Zak Bagans\n}}\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n* Zak Bagans\n* Nick Groff\n* Amber Delly\n}}\n| editor               = {{Plainlist|\n* Zak Bagans\n* Devin Lawrence\n}}\n| location             = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* United Kingdom\n* Italy\n* Mexico\n* [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n* Canada\n* [[Jamaica]]\n* [[Romania]]\n* France\n}}\n| cinematography       = {{Plainlist|\n* Zak Bagans\n* Aaron Goodwin\n* Billy Tolley\n* Jay Wasley\n}}\n| camera               = [[multiple-camera setup|Multiple]]\n| runtime              = 42 minutes\n| company              = MY Tupelo Entertainment\n| distributor          = \n| picture_format       = [[1080i]] [[High-definition television|HDTV]]\n| audio_format         =\n| first_aired          = {{start date|2008|10|17}}\n| last_aired           = present\n| followed_by          = {{Plain list|\n* ''[[Ghost Adventures: Aftershocks]]'' <small>(2014{{en dash}}2016)</small>\n}}\n| related              = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Paranormal Challenge]]''\n* ''[[Deadly Possessions]]''\n* ''[[Paranormal Lockdown]]''\n* ''[[Expedition Unknown]]''\n* ''[[Ghost Nation (TV series)|Ghost Nation]]''\n* ''[[Kindred Spirits (TV series)|Kindred Spirits]]''\n}}\n| website              = http://www.travelchannel.com/TV_Shows/Ghost_Adventures/\n| network              = [[Travel Channel]]\n}}\n'''''Ghost Adventures''''' is an American [[paranormal television|paranormal]] [[documentary]] and [[reality television]] series that premiered on October 17, 2008, on the [[Travel Channel]]. The program follows [[Ghost hunting|ghost hunters]] [[Zak Bagans]], [[Nick Groff]] (until season 10), and Aaron Goodwin as they investigate locations that are reported to be [[List of reportedly haunted locations|haunted]].\n\n==Premise==\n''Ghost Adventures'' began as an [[independent film]], produced in a [[documentary]] style. It was filmed in 2004 and produced by 4Reel Productions in 2006. The [[Syfy|SciFi Channel]] premiered 4Reel's ''Ghost Adventures'' on July 25, 2007. The documentary centered on the trio's investigation of alleged [[paranormal activity]] in and around [[Virginia City, Nevada]], including the [[Goldfield Hotel]] in [[Goldfield, Nevada]]. The crew returned there during the series' fourth, fifth, and seventh seasons.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Old Washoe Club & Chollar Mine |episodelink=List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep3.06 |series=Ghost Adventures |network=[[Travel Channel]] |airdate=December 4, 2009 |season=3 |number=6}}</ref> The series is produced by MY-Tupelo Entertainment (a [[merger]] of MY Entertainment and Tupelo-Honey Productions).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118016866.html?categoryid=14&cs=1&nid=2562 |title=MY-Tupelo scores orders |last=Weisman |first=Jon |date=March 24, 2010 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[PMC (company)|Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref>\n\n===Methodology===\n{{sources|section|date=December 2019}}\n[[Zak Bagans]], [[Nick Groff]] (seasons 1\u201310), Aaron Goodwin, Billy Tolley, and Jay Wasley investigate [[reportedly haunted locations]], hoping to collect visual or auditory evidence of [[paranormal activity]]. Each episode begins with the crew touring the investigation site with its owners or caretakers. These introductions typically include Bagans's voice-overs of the site's history as well as interviews with people who claim to have witnessed [[paranormal phenomena]] there. On the basis of these interviews, the crew place X's with black or gray tape at the sites of some serious alleged paranormal activity. They later return to these spots in order to set up static night-vision cameras to try and film it happening.\n\nAfter completing the walk-through, they discuss their strategy, then are locked in the location overnight, which they believe will prevent \"audio contamination\" and extraneous shadows. They use a variety of equipment, including digital thermometers, [[electromagnetic field]] (EMF) [[EMF measurement|meters]], handheld digital video cameras, audio recorders, the Ovilus device, point of view cameras, and infrared night-vision cameras in an effort to capture evidence of ghosts. The members sometimes place objects and shout verbal taunts they believe ghosts might move or respond to.\n\nThe video and audio collected during each investigation is analyzed after the investigation, and the whole thing is cut down to fit one hour. The most prominent pieces of evidence found are then presented at the appropriate times they happened during the investigation and each one is explained. \n\nDuring the series, the crew claims to have captured and experienced various [[Forteana|Fortean phenomena]], which they say include simultaneous equipment malfunctions such as battery drain, voltage spikes, fluctuations in electromagnetic fields, sudden changes in temperature (such as [[Cold spot (paranormal)|cold spot]]s), unexplained noises, [[electronic voice phenomenon|electronic voice phenomena]] (EVP), and [[ghost|apparitions]].\n\nThe crew also claim to have recorded [[spirit possession]]s on video. Bagans believes that he was possessed at the [[Preston School of Industry]] and at [[Poveglia]] Island in Italy. Groff claims that he was overtaken by a \"dark energy\" at the [[Moon River Brewing Company]]. Goodwin claims he was \"[[Demonic possession|under the influence of a dark spirit]]\" at [[Bobby Mackey's Music World]] and [[Winchester Mystery House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themortonreport.com/entertainment/television/ghost-adventures-aaron-goodwin/|title=Stalking Spirits with Ghost Adventures' Aaron Goodwin|author=Eric Olsen|work=The Morton Report|date=October 3, 2011}}</ref> Goodwin is often left alone in the alleged \"hotspots\" during lockdowns to see how the spirits will react to Goodwin being alone.<ref name=\"aol\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aolnews.com/weird-news/article/haunted-hotel-spooks-ghost-adventures-stars/19568083?sms_ss=twitter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180902084226/http://www.aolnews.com/weird-news/article/haunted-hotel-spooks-ghost-adventures-stars/19568083?sms_ss=twitter |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 2, 2018 |title=Haunted Hotel Spooks 'Ghost Adventures' Stars |last=Moye |first=David |date=July 26, 2010 |work=AOL News |publisher=[[AOL]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesdaily.com/archives/article_a5bcf8dc-bf76-5f61-81fa-b553877ff29e.html|title=Be a paranormal investigator|last=Harris|first=Franklin|date=January 28, 2010|work=[[TimesDaily]] and the [[Decatur Daily]]|publisher=Tennessee Valley Printing Co.|accessdate=February 16, 2010|location=Alabama}}</ref>\n\n==Team members==\n{{inc-video}}\n*[[Zak Bagans]] (2008\u2013present)\n*Aaron Goodwin (2008\u2013present)\n*Billy Tolley (2009\u2013present)\n*Jay Wasley (2009\u2013present)\n\n===Former===\n*[[Nick Groff]] (2008\u20132014)\n\nThe following people have appeared as recurring guests in the show as part of the GAC:\n* Bill Chappell (2010\u20132014)\n* Mark and Debby Constantino (2008\u20132011; until their passing away)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3249859/Ghost-Adventures-star-shot-estranged-wife-s-roommate-head-hours-couple-dead-SWAT-stand-off.html|title=Ghost-hunting couple and housemate were all shot in the head: Police|publisher=|date=September 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Celebrity guests===\n''Ghost Adventures'' has involved celebrities who have participated in the investigations or appeared as eyewitnesses:\n{{columns\n|col1=\n*The Real Hollywood Ghost Hunters ([[Kane Hodder]], [[R. A. Mihailoff]], and [[Rick McCallum]]): \"[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep41|Pico House]]\" episode\n*[[Brendan Schaub]] \u2013 \"[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep67|Peabody-Whitehead Mansion]]\" episode\n*[[Chad Lindberg]] \u2013 \"[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep68|Return to Linda Vista Hospital]]\" episode\n*[[Vince Neil]] \u2013 \"[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep70|The Riviera Hotel]]\" episode\n*[[Jamie Gold]] \u2013 \"The Riviera Hotel\" episode\n|col1width=50%\n|col2=\n*[[Loretta Lynn]] \u2013 \"[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep53|Loretta Lynn's Plantation House]]\" episode\n*[[Brit Morgan]] \u2013 \"[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep87|Glen Tavern Inn]]\" episode\n*[[Mimi Page]] \u2013 \"Glen Tavern Inn\" episode\n*[[Post Malone]] \u2013 \"The Slaughter House\" episode\n*[[Ciaran O'Keeffe]] \u2013 \"Hellfire Caves\" episode\n|col2width=50%\n}}\n\n==Series overview==\n===Episodes===\n{{Main|List of Ghost Adventures episodes}}\n{{:List of Ghost Adventures episodes}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Controversies===\nIn the [[Halloween]] special titled ''Ghost Adventures Live'', which was broadcast from the [[Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum]] on October 30, 2009, controversy arose when Robert Bess, inventor of the Parabot Containment Chamber (said to attract and empower spirits using energy, giving them form), claims to have had an [[EMF meter]] knocked violently out of his hands.  However, upon investigation of the video, it was found that he had actually thrown it.{{cn|date=December 2019}} In the November 6, 2009, follow-up ''Ghost Adventures Live: Post Mortem'', hosts Bagans and Groff reviewed the video and concluded that they couldn't claim any paranormal explanation for the incident.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\n== Related productions ==\n=== Spin-offs ===\n====''Ghost Adventures: Aftershocks''====\n{{Main|Ghost Adventures: Aftershocks}}\n''Ghost Adventures: Aftershocks'' is a series that premiered on Saturday April 26, 2014, on the Travel Channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghostadventurescrew.com/web/episodes/aftershock/|title=Ghost Adventures Aftershocks Home Page|accessdate=October 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523025752/http://www.ghostadventurescrew.com/web/episodes/aftershock/|archive-date=May 23, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> There were 13 episodes announced for the first season and second season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/84535/zak-bagans-new-book-haunted-scaring-shelf-soon/|title=Zak Bagans' New Book I Am Haunted Scaring Up Your Shelf Soon!|publisher=|accessdate=October 25, 2014}}</ref> Zak Bagans interviews former Ghost Adventures interviewees to find out how their lives have changed since those GAC \"lockdowns\"/investigations from the past. Any new audio and/or video evidence that wasn't shown before, in previous Ghost Adventures episodes, are also revealed.\n\n====''Ghost Adventures: Screaming Room!''==== \n\n''Ghost Adventures: Screaming Room!'' premiered on January 2, 2020, with Zak, Aaron, Jay and Billy opening up to viewers in their screening\u00a0room\u00a0(a.k.a. \"screaming room\") to watch their favorite episodes.<ref>https://bloody-disgusting.com/tv/3596920/trailer-zak-bagans-friends-revisit-scariest-moments-new-series-ghost-adventures-screaming-room/</ref>\n\n=== Other ===\n====''Paranormal Challenge''====\n{{Main|Paranormal Challenge}}\n''Paranormal Challenge'' is a competitive paranormal reality show that premiered on June 17, 2011, on the Travel Channel, with one season aired to date. The show is hosted by Zak Bagans, who challenges ghost hunters from around the United States to go head-to-head in a weekly competition to gather paranormal evidence by spending a night in reportedly haunted locations in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=About the Show Paranormal Challenge|url=http://www.travelchannel.com/TV_Shows/Paranormal_Challenge/About_The_Show/Paranormal_Challenge|website=Travel Channel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027183603/http://www.travelchannel.com/TV_Shows/Paranormal_Challenge/About_The_Show/Paranormal_Challenge|archive-date=October 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====''Deadly Possessions''====\n{{Main|Deadly Possessions}}\n''Deadly Possessions''(also known as Ghost Adventures:Artifacts) is a series that premiered on April 2, 2016, on the Travel Channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.travelchannel.com/shows/deadly-possessions|title=Zak Bagans' 'Deadly Possessions'|website=Travel Channel|access-date=April 4, 2016}}</ref> The series aired one season and features Zak Bagans as he gathers artifacts for his new museum in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]. The show reveals the dark history of the items, as well as associated paranormal claims.\n\n==Distribution==\n===International===\n''Ghost Adventures'' is currently on air at the following countries and channels:\n* {{AUS}} on [[A&E Australia]], [[Foxtel Go]]<ref>With [[Foxtel]] having their own online catchup service called [[Foxtel GO]]</ref>\n* {{CAN}} on [[Travel + Escape]] and [[DTour]]\n* {{GBR}} on [[Really (TV channel)|Really]]\n* {{ITA}} on [[AXN Sci Fi]] and [[DMAX (Italy)|DMAX]]\n* {{POL}} on FOKUS TV\n* {{FRA}} on [[Plan\u00e8te+]] A&E\n* {{ESP}} on [[Mega (Spanish television channel)|Mega]]\n* {{GER}} on A&E Germany\n* {{NED}} on Spike\n* {{BEL}} on Spike\n* {{CZE}} on Prima ZOOM\n* {{USA}} on [[Travel Channel]]\n* {{PHI}} on Travel Channel \u2013 [[Sky Cable]] and Cignal PH\n* {{RSA}} on Travel Channel \u2013 [[DStv]]\n* {{THA}} on [[TrueVisions]]\n* {{NZL}} on [[The Learning Channel]]\n\n==Home media releases==\nThe documentary which the series was based on was released on [[DVD]] by [[Echo Bridge Home Entertainment]] on October 5, 2010. Seasons 1 and 2 were released on DVD on August 18, 2009.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ghost hunting]]\n*[[List of ghost films]]\n*[[Paranormal television]]\n*''[[The Dead Files]]''\n*''[[Kindred Spirits (TV series)|Kindred Spirits]]''\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.paranormalunderground.net/site/?p=1210 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130221223157/http://www.paranormalunderground.net/site/?p=1210 |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 21, 2013 |title=Fear No Evil |last=Mannen |first=Scott |date=June 2009 |publisher=Ghost Knight Media |author2=Karen Frazier |work=Paranormal Underground }}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117983174.html?categoryid=1071&cs=1&query=ghost+adventures|title=Yudin, Travel team on 'Ghost'|last=Dempsey|first=John|date=March 30, 2008|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.travelchannel.com/shows/ghost-adventures}} \n*{{IMDb title|1319900}}\n*{{tv.com show|ghost-adventures|Ghost Adventures}}\n*{{thetvdb|83929}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghost Adventures}}\n[[Category:Ghost Adventures]]\n[[Category:Travel Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:Paranormal reality television series]]\n[[Category:2008 American television series debuts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Ghost Adventures\n| image                = ghost adventures.jpg\n| show_name_2          =\n| genre                = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Paranormal]]\n* [[Documentary]]\n* [[Reality television]]\n}}\n| creator              = [[Zak Bagans]]\n| developer            =\n| writer               = {{Plainlist|\n* Zak Bagans\n* Devin Lawrence\n* Jeff Belanger\n}}\n| presenter            =\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* Zak Bagans\n* Aaron Goodwin\n* Billy Tolley\n* Jay Wasley\n* [[Nick Groff]] <small>(2008\u20132014)</small>\n}}\n| num_seasons          = 12\n| num_episodes         = 219 (plus the 47 specials not included in list)\n| list_episodes        = List of Ghost Adventures episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* Daniel A. Schwartz\n* Joe Townley\n* Michael Yudin\n* Nick Groff\n* Zak Bagans\n}}\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n* Zak Bagans\n* Nick Groff\n* Amber Delly\n}}\n| editor               = {{Plainlist|\n* Zak Bagans\n* Devin Lawrence\n}}\n| location             = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* United Kingdom\n* Italy\n* Mexico\n* [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n* Canada\n* [[Jamaica]]\n* [[Romania]]\n* France\n}}\n| cinematography       = {{Plainlist|\n* Zak Bagans\n* Aaron Goodwin\n* Billy Tolley\n* Jay Wasley\n}}\n| camera               = [[multiple-camera setup|Multiple]]\n| runtime              = 42 minutes\n| company              = MY Tupelo Entertainment\n| distributor          = \n| picture_format       = [[1080i]] [[High-definition television|HDTV]]\n| audio_format         =\n| first_aired          = {{start date|2008|10|17}}\n| last_aired           = present\n| followed_by          = {{Plain list|\n* ''[[Ghost Adventures: Aftershocks]]'' <small>(2014{{en dash}}2016)</small>\n}}\n| related              = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Paranormal Challenge]]''\n* ''[[Deadly Possessions]]''\n* ''[[Paranormal Lockdown]]''\n* ''[[Expedition Unknown]]''\n* ''[[Ghost Nation (TV series)|Ghost Nation]]''\n* ''[[Kindred Spirits (TV series)|Kindred Spirits]]''\n}}\n| website              = http://www.travelchannel.com/TV_Shows/Ghost_Adventures/\n| network              = [[Travel Channel]]\n}}\n'''''Ghost Adventures''''' is an American [[paranormal television|paranormal]] [[documentary]] and [[reality television]] series that premiered on October 17, 2008, on the [[Travel Channel]]. The program follows [[Ghost hunting|ghost hunters]] [[Zak Bagans]], [[Nick Groff]] (until season 10), and Aaron Goodwin as they investigate locations that are reported to be [[List of reportedly haunted locations|haunted]].\n\n==Premise==\n''Ghost Adventures'' began as an [[independent film]], produced in a [[documentary]] style. It was filmed in 2004 and produced by 4Reel Productions in 2006. The [[Syfy|SciFi Channel]] premiered 4Reel's ''Ghost Adventures'' on July 25, 2007. The documentary centered on the trio's investigation of alleged [[paranormal activity]] in and around [[Virginia City, Nevada]], including the [[Goldfield Hotel]] in [[Goldfield, Nevada]]. The crew returned there during the series' fourth, fifth, and seventh seasons.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Old Washoe Club & Chollar Mine |episodelink=List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep3.06 |series=Ghost Adventures |network=[[Travel Channel]] |airdate=December 4, 2009 |season=3 |number=6}}</ref> The series is produced by MY-Tupelo Entertainment (a [[merger]] of MY Entertainment and Tupelo-Honey Productions).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118016866.html?categoryid=14&cs=1&nid=2562 |title=MY-Tupelo scores orders |last=Weisman |first=Jon |date=March 24, 2010 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[PMC (company)|Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref>\n\n===Methodology===\n{{sources|section|date=December 2019}}\n[[Zak Bagans]], [[Nick Groff]] (seasons 1\u201310), Aaron Goodwin, Billy Tolley, and Jay Wasley investigate [[reportedly haunted locations]], hoping to collect visual or auditory evidence of [[paranormal activity]]. Each episode begins with the crew touring the investigation site with its owners or caretakers. These introductions typically include Bagans's voice-overs of the site's history as well as interviews with people who claim to have witnessed [[paranormal phenomena]] there. On the basis of these interviews, the crew place X's with black or gray tape at the sites of some serious alleged paranormal activity. They later return to these spots in order to set up static night-vision cameras to try and film it happening.\n\nAfter completing the walk-through, they discuss their strategy, then are locked in the location overnight, which they believe will prevent \"audio contamination\" and extraneous shadows. They use a variety of equipment, including digital thermometers, [[electromagnetic field]] (EMF) [[EMF measurement|meters]], handheld digital video cameras, audio recorders, the Ovilus device, point of view cameras, and infrared night-vision cameras in an effort to capture evidence of ghosts. The members sometimes place objects and shout verbal taunts they believe ghosts might move or respond to.\n\nThe video and audio collected during each investigation is analyzed after the investigation, and the whole thing is cut down to fit one hour. The most prominent pieces of evidence found are then presented at the appropriate times they happened during the investigation and each one is explained. \n\nDuring the series, the crew claims to have captured and experienced various [[Forteana|Fortean phenomena]], which they say include simultaneous equipment malfunctions such as battery drain, voltage spikes, fluctuations in electromagnetic fields, sudden changes in temperature (such as [[Cold spot (paranormal)|cold spot]]s), unexplained noises, [[electronic voice phenomenon|electronic voice phenomena]] (EVP), and [[ghost|apparitions]].\n\nThe crew also claim to have recorded [[spirit possession]]s on video. Bagans believes that he was possessed at the [[Preston School of Industry]] and at [[Poveglia]] Island in Italy. Groff claims that he was overtaken by a \"dark energy\" at the [[Moon River Brewing Company]]. Goodwin claims he was \"[[Demonic possession|under the influence of a dark spirit]]\" at [[Bobby Mackey's Music World]] and [[Winchester Mystery House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themortonreport.com/entertainment/television/ghost-adventures-aaron-goodwin/|title=Stalking Spirits with Ghost Adventures' Aaron Goodwin|author=Eric Olsen|work=The Morton Report|date=October 3, 2011}}</ref> Goodwin is often left alone in the alleged \"hotspots\" during lockdowns to see how the spirits will react to Goodwin being alone.<ref name=\"aol\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aolnews.com/weird-news/article/haunted-hotel-spooks-ghost-adventures-stars/19568083?sms_ss=twitter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180902084226/http://www.aolnews.com/weird-news/article/haunted-hotel-spooks-ghost-adventures-stars/19568083?sms_ss=twitter |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 2, 2018 |title=Haunted Hotel Spooks 'Ghost Adventures' Stars |last=Moye |first=David |date=July 26, 2010 |work=AOL News |publisher=[[AOL]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesdaily.com/archives/article_a5bcf8dc-bf76-5f61-81fa-b553877ff29e.html|title=Be a paranormal investigator|last=Harris|first=Franklin|date=January 28, 2010|work=[[TimesDaily]] and the [[Decatur Daily]]|publisher=Tennessee Valley Printing Co.|accessdate=February 16, 2010|location=Alabama}}</ref>\n\n==Team members==\n{{inc-video}}\n*[[Zak Bagans]] (2008\u2013present)\n*Aaron Goodwin (2008\u2013present)\n*Billy Tolley (2009\u2013present)\n*Jay Wasley (2009\u2013present)\n\n===Former===\n*[[Nick Groff]] (2008\u20132014)\n\nThe following people have appeared as recurring guests in the show as part of the GAC:\n* Bill Chappell (2010\u20132014)\n* Mark and Debby Constantino (2008\u20132011; until their passing away)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3249859/Ghost-Adventures-star-shot-estranged-wife-s-roommate-head-hours-couple-dead-SWAT-stand-off.html|title=Ghost-hunting couple and housemate were all shot in the head: Police|publisher=|date=September 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Celebrity guests===\n''Ghost Adventures'' has involved celebrities who have participated in the investigations or appeared as eyewitnesses:\n{{columns\n|col1=\n*The Real Hollywood Ghost Hunters ([[Kane Hodder]], [[R. A. Mihailoff]], and [[Rick McCallum]]): \"[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep41|Pico House]]\" episode\n*[[Brendan Schaub]] \u2013 \"[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep67|Peabody-Whitehead Mansion]]\" episode\n*[[Chad Lindberg]] \u2013 \"[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep68|Return to Linda Vista Hospital]]\" episode\n*[[Vince Neil]] \u2013 \"[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep70|The Riviera Hotel]]\" episode\n*[[Jamie Gold]] \u2013 \"The Riviera Hotel\" episode\n|col1width=50%\n|col2=\n*[[Loretta Lynn]] \u2013 \"[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep53|Loretta Lynn's Plantation House]]\" episode\n*[[Brit Morgan]] \u2013 \"[[List of Ghost Adventures episodes#ep87|Glen Tavern Inn]]\" episode\n*[[Mimi Page]] \u2013 \"Glen Tavern Inn\" episode\n*[[Post Malone]] \u2013 \"The Slaughter House\" episode\n*[[Ciaran O'Keeffe]] \u2013 \"Hellfire Caves\" episode\n|col2width=50%\n}}\n\n==Series overview==\n===Episodes===\n{{Main|List of Ghost Adventures episodes}}\n{{:List of Ghost Adventures episodes}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Controversies===\nIn the [[Halloween]] special titled ''Ghost Adventures Live'', which was broadcast from the [[Trans-Allegheny Lunatic Asylum]] on October 30, 2009, controversy arose when Robert Bess, inventor of the Parabot Containment Chamber (said to attract and empower spirits using energy, giving them form), claims to have had an [[EMF meter]] knocked violently out of his hands.  However, upon investigation of the video, it was found that he had actually thrown it.{{cn|date=December 2019}} In the November 6, 2009, follow-up ''Ghost Adventures Live: Post Mortem'', hosts Bagans and Groff reviewed the video and concluded that they couldn't claim any paranormal explanation for the incident.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\n== Related productions ==\n=== Spin-offs ===\n====''Ghost Adventures: Aftershocks''====\n{{Main|Ghost Adventures: Aftershocks}}\n''Ghost Adventures: Aftershocks'' is a series that premiered on Saturday April 26, 2014, on the Travel Channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghostadventurescrew.com/web/episodes/aftershock/|title=Ghost Adventures Aftershocks Home Page|accessdate=October 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523025752/http://www.ghostadventurescrew.com/web/episodes/aftershock/|archive-date=May 23, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> There were 13 episodes announced for the first season and second season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/84535/zak-bagans-new-book-haunted-scaring-shelf-soon/|title=Zak Bagans' New Book I Am Haunted Scaring Up Your Shelf Soon!|publisher=|accessdate=October 25, 2014}}</ref> Zak Bagans interviews former Ghost Adventures interviewees to find out how their lives have changed since those GAC \"lockdowns\"/investigations from the past. Any new audio and/or video evidence that wasn't shown before, in previous Ghost Adventures episodes, are also revealed.\n\n====''Ghost Adventures: Screaming Room!''==== \n\n''Ghost Adventures: Screaming Room!'' premiered on January 2, 2020, with Zak, Aaron, Jay and Billy opening up to viewers in their screening\u00a0room\u00a0(a.k.a. \"screaming room\") to watch their favorite episodes.<ref>https://bloody-disgusting.com/tv/3596920/trailer-zak-bagans-friends-revisit-scariest-moments-new-series-ghost-adventures-screaming-room/</ref>\n\n=== Other ===\n====''Paranormal Challenge''====\n{{Main|Paranormal Challenge}}\n''Paranormal Challenge'' is a competitive paranormal reality show that premiered on June 17, 2011, on the Travel Channel, with one season aired to date. The show is hosted by Zak Bagans, who challenges ghost hunters from around the United States to go head-to-head in a weekly competition to gather paranormal evidence by spending a night in reportedly haunted locations in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=About the Show Paranormal Challenge|url=http://www.travelchannel.com/TV_Shows/Paranormal_Challenge/About_The_Show/Paranormal_Challenge|website=Travel Channel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027183603/http://www.travelchannel.com/TV_Shows/Paranormal_Challenge/About_The_Show/Paranormal_Challenge|archive-date=October 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====''Deadly Possessions''====\n{{Main|Deadly Possessions}}\n''Deadly Possessions''(also known as Ghost Adventures:Artifacts) is a series that premiered on April 2, 2016, on the Travel Channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.travelchannel.com/shows/deadly-possessions|title=Zak Bagans' 'Deadly Possessions'|website=Travel Channel|access-date=April 4, 2016}}</ref> The series aired one season and features Zak Bagans as he gathers artifacts for his new museum in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]. The show reveals the dark history of the items, as well as associated paranormal claims.\n\n==Distribution==\n===International===\n''Ghost Adventures'' is currently on air at the following countries and channels:\n* {{AUS}} on [[A&E Australia]], [[Foxtel Go]]<ref>With [[Foxtel]] having their own online catchup service called [[Foxtel GO]]</ref>\n* {{CAN}} on [[Travel + Escape]] and [[DTour]]\n* {{GBR}} on [[Really (TV channel)|Really]]\n* {{ITA}} on [[AXN Sci Fi]] and [[DMAX (Italy)|DMAX]]\n* {{POL}} on FOKUS TV\n* {{FRA}} on [[Plan\u00e8te+]] A&E\n* {{ESP}} on [[Mega (Spanish television channel)|Mega]]\n* {{GER}} on A&E Germany\n* {{NED}} on Spike\n* {{BEL}} on Spike\n* {{CZE}} on Prima ZOOM\n* {{USA}} on [[Travel Channel]]\n* {{PHI}} on Travel Channel \u2013 [[Sky Cable]] and Cignal PH\n* {{RSA}} on Travel Channel \u2013 [[DStv]]\n* {{THA}} on [[TrueVisions]]\n* {{NZL}} on [[The Learning Channel]]\n\n==Home media releases==\nThe documentary which the series was based on was released on [[DVD]] by [[Echo Bridge Home Entertainment]] on October 5, 2010. Seasons 1 and 2 were released on DVD on August 18, 2009.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ghost hunting]]\n*[[List of ghost films]]\n*[[Paranormal television]]\n*''[[The Dead Files]]''\n*''[[Kindred Spirits (TV series)|Kindred Spirits]]''\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.paranormalunderground.net/site/?p=1210 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130221223157/http://www.paranormalunderground.net/site/?p=1210 |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 21, 2013 |title=Fear No Evil |last=Mannen |first=Scott |date=June 2009 |publisher=Ghost Knight Media |author2=Karen Frazier |work=Paranormal Underground }}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117983174.html?categoryid=1071&cs=1&query=ghost+adventures|title=Yudin, Travel team on 'Ghost'|last=Dempsey|first=John|date=March 30, 2008|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.travelchannel.com/shows/ghost-adventures}} \n*{{IMDb title|1319900}}\n*{{tv.com show|ghost-adventures|Ghost Adventures}}\n*{{thetvdb|83929}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghost Adventures}}\n[[Category:Ghost Adventures]]\n[[Category:Travel Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:Paranormal reality television series]]\n[[Category:2008 American television series debuts]]\n", "name_user": "192.69.180.126", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(true empath truth that you and your team completely miss thought you should know you and your team miss so much)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghost_Adventures"}
{"title_page": "Sentimental Destinies", "text_new": "{{short description|2000 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sentimental Destinies\n| image          = Les Destin\u00e9es sentimentales.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Olivier Assayas]]\n| producer       = [[Bruno P\u00e9sery]]\n| writer         = Olivier Assayas<br>[[Jacques Chardonne]]<br>[[Jacques Fieschi]]\n| starring       = [[Emmanuelle B\u00e9art]]<br>[[Charles Berling]]<br>[[Isabelle Huppert]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Eric Gautier]]\n| editing        = Luc Barnier\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|2000|5|17|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 180 minutes\n| country        = France<br>Switzerland\n| language       = French\n| budget         = $14.9 million\n| gross          = $4.3 million<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=2461|title=Les Destin\u00e9es sentimentales (Les Destin\u00e9es) (2000) - JPBox-Office|website=www.jpbox-office.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Sentimental Destinies''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Les Destin\u00e9es sentimentales'''}}) is a 2000 French [[drama film]] directed by [[Olivier Assayas]]. It was entered into the [[2000 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/10529/year/2000.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Sentimental Destinies |accessdate=10 October 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nBased on the novel  of the same name by [[Jacques Chardonne]], the film is set in the early 20th century. The story covers thirty years in the life of  Jean, a Protestant  minister who leaves his wife (Isabelle Huppert) for Pauline (Emmanuelle B\u00e9art), the niece of one of his parishioners. Abandoning his career in the church, he sets up home with her in Switzerland. Following the death of an uncle he moves to [[Limoges]], where he takes over the running of  the family [[porcelain]] factory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/12/06/les_destinees_sentimentales_2000_review.shtml|title=Les Destin\u00e9es Sentimentales (2000)|publisher=BBC|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/85478/destinees.sentimentales|title=Les Destin\u00e9es Sentimentales |author=Bradshaw, Peter|work=The Guardian|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Emmanuelle B\u00e9art]] as Pauline Pommerel\n* [[Charles Berling]] as Jean Barnery\n* [[Isabelle Huppert]] as Nathalie Barnery\n* [[Olivier Perrier]] as Philippe Pommerel\n* [[Dominique Reymond]] as Julie Desca\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Marcon]] as Paul Desca\n* [[Alexandra London]] as Louise Desca\n* [[Julie Depardieu]] as Marcelle\n* [[Louis-Do de Lencquesaing]] as Arthur Pommerel\n* [[Val\u00e9rie Bonneton]] as Arthur Pommerel's wife\n* [[Pascal Bongard]] as Vouzelles\n* [[Didier Flamand]] as Guy Barnery\n* [[Jean-Baptiste Malartre]] as Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Barnery\n* [[Nicolas Pignon]] as Bavouzet\n* [[Catherine Mouchet]] as Fernande\n* [[Mia Hansen-L\u00f8ve]] as Aline\n\n==See also==\n* [[Isabelle Huppert on screen and stage]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0216689|title=Sentimental Destinies}}\n\n{{Olivier Assayas}}\n\n[[Category:2000 films]]\n[[Category:Swiss films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:2000 drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Olivier Assayas]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Olivier Assayas]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:Swiss drama films]]\n{{2000s-France-film-stub}}\n{{2000s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2000 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sentimental Destinies\n| image          = Les Destin\u00e9es sentimentales.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Olivier Assayas]]\n| producer       = [[Bruno P\u00e9sery]]\n| writer         = Olivier Assayas<br>[[Jacques Chardonne]]<br>[[Jacques Fieschi]]\n| starring       = [[Emmanuelle B\u00e9art]]<br>[[Charles Berling]]<br>[[Isabelle Huppert]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Eric Gautier]]\n| editing        = Luc Barnier\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|2000|5|17|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 180 minutes\n| country        = France<br>Switzerland\n| language       = French\n| budget         = $14.9 million\n| gross          = $4.3 million<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=2461|title=Les Destin\u00e9es sentimentales (Les Destin\u00e9es) (2000) - JPBox-Office|website=www.jpbox-office.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Sentimental Destinies''''' ({{lang-fr|'''Les Destin\u00e9es sentimentales'''}}) is a 2000 French [[drama film]] directed by [[Olivier Assayas]]. It was entered into the [[2000 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/10529/year/2000.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Sentimental Destinies |accessdate=10 October 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nBased on the novel  of the same name by [[Jacques Chardonne]], the film is set in the early 20th century. The story covers thirty years in the life of  Jean, a Protestant  minister who leaves his wife (Isabelle Huppert) for Pauline (Emmanuelle B\u00e9art), the niece of one of his parishioners. Abandoning his career in the church, he sets up home with her in Switzerland. Following the death of an uncle he moves to [[Limoges]], where he takes over the running of  the family [[porcelain]] factory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/12/06/les_destinees_sentimentales_2000_review.shtml|title=Les Destin\u00e9es Sentimentales (2000)|publisher=BBC|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/85478/destinees.sentimentales|title=Les Destin\u00e9es Sentimentales |author=Bradshaw, Peter|work=The Guardian|accessdate=14 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Emmanuelle B\u00e9art]] as Pauline Pommerel\n* [[Charles Berling]] as Jean Barnery\n* [[Isabelle Huppert]] as Nathalie Barnery\n* [[Olivier Perrier]] as Philippe Pommerel\n* [[Dominique Reymond]] as Julie Desca\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Marcon]] as Paul Desca\n* [[Alexandra London]] as Louise Desca\n* [[Julie Depardieu]] as Marcelle\n* [[Louis-Do de Lencquesaing]] as Arthur Pommerel\n* [[Val\u00e9rie Bonneton]] as Arthur Pommerel's wife\n* [[Pascal Bongard]] as Vouzelles\n* [[Didier Flamand]] as Guy Barnery\n* [[Jean-Baptiste Malartre]] as Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Barnery\n* [[Nicolas Pignon]] as Bavouzet\n* [[Catherine Mouchet]] as Fernande\n* [[Mia Hansen-L\u00f8ve]] as Aline\n\n==See also==\n* [[Isabelle Huppert on screen and stage]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0216689|title=Sentimental Destinies}}\n\n{{Olivier Assayas}}\n\n[[Category:2000 films]]\n[[Category:Swiss films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:2000 drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Olivier Assayas]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Olivier Assayas]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:Swiss drama films]]\n{{2000s-France-film-stub}}\n{{2000s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sentimental_Destinies"}
{"title_page": "Cymbidium hookerianum", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Cymbidium hookerianum 2.jpg\n| genus = Cymbidium\n| species = hookerianum\n| authority = Rchb.f. (1866)\n| synonyms =\n* ''Cymbidium grandiflorum'' Griff. (1851)\n* ''Cyperorchis grandiflora'' Schltr. (1924)\n}}\n\n'''''Cymbidium hookerianum''''' (common name ''Hooker's Cymbidium'') is a species of [[orchid]] found in [[India]], [[China]], and [[Vietnam]]. It is distributed widely in [[Bhutan]], especially in the cool temperate forests. \n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Cymbidium hookerianum.jpg|thumb|Illustration of ''Cymbidium hookerianum'']]''Cymbidium hookerianum'' is a species of medium to large size orchid, which prefers cold weather. It is [[epiphytic]] with an ovoid [[pseudobulb]], elongated with ligulate, acuminate, and articulated [[leaves]]. It blooms in a solid [[inflorescence]], sheathed at the base, hanging and arched, 75 cm long, apical with triangular floral [[bracts]] and bearing 6 to 15 [[flowers]], 14 cm long. It has a very fragrant and long-lasting oder. Flowering occurs in late [[winter]] and [[spring (season)|spring]].<ref name=\"Pfahl\">{{cite web |last1=Pfahl |first1=Jay |title=Cymbidium hookerianum |url=http://www.orchidspecies.com/cymhookeriana.htm |website=Internet Orchid Species Photo Encyclopedia |accessdate=7 April 2020 |ref=Pfahl}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nIt is distributed throughout [[Nepal]], [[Bhutan]], and [[Sikkim]] on steep river banks in dense and humid forests or [[oak]] forests, always at heights of 1600 to 2400 meters.<ref name=\"Pfahl\"/>\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n''Cymbidium hookerianum'' was described by [[Heinrich Gustav Reichenbach]] and published in ''[[The Gardeners' Chronicle & Agricultural Gazette]]'' in 1866.<ref name=\"tropicos\">{{Cite web|url=http://legacy.tropicos.org/Name/23513275|title=!Cymbidium hookerianum Rchb. f.|last=|first=|date=|website=Tropicos.org|publisher=Missouri Botanical Garden|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Etymology ===\n'''''Cymbidium''''': The name derives from the [[Greek language|Greek]] word ''kumbos'', which means \"hole, cavity\". This refers to the shape of the base of the lip. According to other scholars it derives from the Greek ''kimbe'', which means boat, for the shape of the ship that the lip assumes.\n\n'''''hookerianum''''': Named in honor of botanist [[Joseph Dalton Hooker]], \"an excellent name too, given with the writer's best wishes as a gratulation for the first new year's day of his Kew directorship, to Dr. Hooker.\" <ref>Reichenbach, Heinrich Gustav. in The Gardeners' Chronicle and Agricultural Gazette. 1866. Page 7. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/26048724]</ref>\n\n..\n\n=== Synonyms ===\n* ''Cymbidium grandiflorum'' Griff. (1851)\n* ''Cyperorchis grandiflora'' ([[Sw.]]) [[Schltr.]] 1924<<ref name=\"Pfahl\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl/record/kew-53229|title=Cymbidium hookerianum Rchb.f.|last=|first=|date=|website=The Plant List|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wcsp.science.kew.org/namedetail.do?name_id=53229|title=Cymbidium hookerianum|last=|first=|date=|website=World Checklist of Selected Plant Families (WCSP)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons-inline|:Cymbidium hookerianum|''Cymbidium hookerianum''}} \n* [http://powo.science.kew.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:625040-1 Cymbidium hookerianum | Plants of the World Onlne]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2705378}}\n\n[[Category:Cymbidium|hookerianum]]\n[[Category:Orchids of India]]\n[[Category:Orchids of China]]\n[[Category:Orchids of Vietnam]]\n\n\n{{Cymbidieae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Cymbidium hookerianum 2.jpg\n| genus = Cymbidium\n| species = hookerianum\n| authority = Rchb.f. (1866)\n| synonyms =\n* ''Cymbidium grandiflorum'' Griff. (1851)\n* ''Cyperorchis grandiflora'' Schltr. (1924)\n}}\n\n'''''Cymbidium hookerianum''''' (common name ''Hooker's Cymbidium'') is a species of [[orchid]] found in [[India]], [[China]], and [[Vietnam]]. It is distributed widely in [[Bhutan]], especially in the cool temperate forests. \n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Cymbidium hookerianum.jpg|thumb|Illustration of ''Cymbidium hookerianum'']]''Cymbidium hookerianum'' is a species of medium to large size orchid, which prefers cold weather. It is [[epiphytic]] with an ovoid [[pseudobulb]], elongated with ligulate, acuminate, and articulated [[leaves]]. It blooms in a solid [[inflorescence]], sheathed at the base, hanging and arched, 75 cm long, apical with triangular floral [[bracts]] and bearing 6 to 15 [[flowers]], 14 cm long. It has a very fragrant and long-lasting oder. Flowering occurs in late [[winter]] and [[spring]].<ref name=\"Pfahl\">{{cite web |last1=Pfahl |first1=Jay |title=Cymbidium hookerianum |url=http://www.orchidspecies.com/cymhookeriana.htm |website=Internet Orchid Species Photo Encyclopedia |accessdate=7 April 2020 |ref=Pfahl}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nIt is distributed throughout [[Nepal]], [[Bhutan]], and [[Sikkim]] on steep river banks in dense and humid forests or [[oak]] forests, always at heights of 1600 to 2400 meters.<ref name=\"Pfahl\"/>\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n''Cymbidium hookerianum'' was described by [[Heinrich Gustav Reichenbach]] and published in ''[[The Gardeners' Chronicle & Agricultural Gazette]]'' in 1866.<ref name=\"tropicos\">{{Cite web|url=http://legacy.tropicos.org/Name/23513275|title=!Cymbidium hookerianum Rchb. f.|last=|first=|date=|website=Tropicos.org|publisher=Missouri Botanical Garden|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Etymology ===\n'''''Cymbidium''''': The name derives from the [[Greek]] word ''kumbos'', which means \"hole, cavity\". This refers to the shape of the base of the lip. According to other scholars it derives from the Greek ''kimbe'', which means boat, for the shape of the ship that the lip assumes.\n\n'''''hookerianum''''': Named in honor of botanist [[Joseph Dalton Hooker]], \"an excellent name too, given with the writer's best wishes as a gratulation for the first new year's day of his Kew directorship, to Dr. Hooker.\" <ref>Reichenbach, Heinrich Gustav. in The Gardeners' Chronicle and Agricultural Gazette. 1866. Page 7. [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/26048724]</ref>\n\n..\n\n=== Synonyms ===\n* ''Cymbidium grandiflorum'' Griff. (1851)\n* ''Cyperorchis grandiflora'' ([[Sw.]]) [[Schltr.]] 1924<<ref name=\"Pfahl\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl/record/kew-53229|title=Cymbidium hookerianum Rchb.f.|last=|first=|date=|website=The Plant List|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wcsp.science.kew.org/namedetail.do?name_id=53229|title=Cymbidium hookerianum|last=|first=|date=|website=World Checklist of Selected Plant Families (WCSP)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons-inline|:Cymbidium hookerianum|''Cymbidium hookerianum''}} \n* [http://powo.science.kew.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:625040-1 Cymbidium hookerianum | Plants of the World Onlne]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2705378}}\n\n[[Category:Cymbidium|hookerianum]]\n[[Category:Orchids of India]]\n[[Category:Orchids of China]]\n[[Category:Orchids of Vietnam]]\n\n\n{{Cymbidieae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:spring\u2192spring (season),Greek\u2192Greek language", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cymbidium_hookerianum"}
{"title_page": "Seventeen Times Cecile Cassard", "text_new": "{{short description|2002 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Seventeen Times Cecile Cassard\n| image          = 17 fois C\u00e9cile Cassard.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Christophe Honor\u00e9]]\n| producer       = Philippe Jacquier<br>[[B\u00e9atrice Mauduit]]\n| writer         = Christophe Honor\u00e9\n| starring       = [[B\u00e9atrice Dalle]]\n| music          = Alex Beaupain\n| cinematography = R\u00e9my Chevrin\n| editing        = Chantal Hymans\n| distributor    = ARP S\u00e9lection\n| released       = {{film date|2002|7|10|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| budget         = $2.3 million\n| gross          = $360,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=1962|title=17 fois C\u00e9cile Cassard (2002)- JPBox-Office|publisher=|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Seventeen Times Cecile Cassard''''' ({{lang-fr|'''17 fois C\u00e9cile Cassard'''}}) is a 2002 French [[drama film]] directed by [[Christophe Honor\u00e9]]. It was screened in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[2002 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/3167851/year/2002.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Carnage |accessdate=30 October 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[B\u00e9atrice Dalle]] as C\u00e9cile Cassard\n* [[Romain Duris]] as Matthieu\n* [[Jeanne Balibar]] as Edith\n* [[Ange Ruz\u00e9]] as Erwan\n* [[Johan Oderio-Robles]] as Lucas\n* [[Tiago Mana\u00efa]] as Tiago\n* [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Kircher]] as Thierry\n* [[Julien Collet]] as St\u00e9phane\n* [[J\u00e9r\u00e9my Sanguinetti]] as Julien\n* [[Marie Bunel]] as The teacher\n* [[Assaad Bouab]] as The waiter\n* [[Fabio Zenoni]] as The porch man\n* [[Robert Cantarella]] as The cemetery man\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|id=0296591|title=Seventeen Times Cecile Cassard}}\n\n{{Christophe Honor\u00e9}}\n\n[[Category:2002 films]]\n[[Category:2002 drama films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Christophe Honor\u00e9]]\n[[Category:2002 directorial debut films]]\n\n\n{{2000s-France-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2002 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Seventeen Times Cecile Cassard\n| image          = 17 fois C\u00e9cile Cassard.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Christophe Honor\u00e9]]\n| producer       = Philippe Jacquier<br>[[B\u00e9atrice Mauduit]]\n| writer         = Christophe Honor\u00e9\n| starring       = [[B\u00e9atrice Dalle]]\n| music          = Alex Beaupain\n| cinematography = R\u00e9my Chevrin\n| editing        = Chantal Hymans\n| distributor    = ARP S\u00e9lection\n| released       = {{film date|2002|7|10|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| budget         = $2.3 million\n| gross          = $360,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=1962|title=17 fois C\u00e9cile Cassard (2002)- JPBox-Office|publisher=|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Seventeen Times Cecile Cassard''''' ({{lang-fr|'''17 fois C\u00e9cile Cassard'''}}) is a 2002 French [[drama film]] directed by [[Christophe Honor\u00e9]]. It was screened in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[2002 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/3167851/year/2002.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Carnage |accessdate=30 October 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[B\u00e9atrice Dalle]] as C\u00e9cile Cassard\n* [[Romain Duris]] as Matthieu\n* [[Jeanne Balibar]] as Edith\n* [[Ange Ruz\u00e9]] as Erwan\n* [[Johan Oderio-Robles]] as Lucas\n* [[Tiago Mana\u00efa]] as Tiago\n* [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Kircher]] as Thierry\n* [[Julien Collet]] as St\u00e9phane\n* [[J\u00e9r\u00e9my Sanguinetti]] as Julien\n* [[Marie Bunel]] as The teacher\n* [[Assaad Bouab]] as The waiter\n* [[Fabio Zenoni]] as The porch man\n* [[Robert Cantarella]] as The cemetery man\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|id=0296591|title=Seventeen Times Cecile Cassard}}\n\n{{Christophe Honor\u00e9}}\n\n[[Category:2002 films]]\n[[Category:2002 drama films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Christophe Honor\u00e9]]\n[[Category:2002 directorial debut films]]\n\n\n{{2000s-France-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seventeen_Times_Cecile_Cassard"}
{"title_page": "Maureen Johnson", "text_new": "{{short description|American author of young adult fiction}}\n{{about|the author|the character from ''Rent''|Rent (musical)#Maureen Johnson|character by Robert A. Heinlein|Maureen Johnson (Heinlein character)}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image = American author Maureen Johnson at LA Times Festival of Books 2012.png\n| imagesize = \n| name = Maureen Johnson\n| pseudonym = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1973|02|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania, United States\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = Novelist\n| nationality = United States\n| period = 2004\u2013present\n| genre = [[Young adult literature|Young adult fiction]], [[Mystery fiction]]\n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| signature  = a maureen johnson signature.svg\n| website = {{URL|http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com}}\n}}\n'''Maureen Johnson''' (born February 16, 1973) is an American author of [[Young adult literature|young adult fiction]]. Her published novels include ''13 Little Blue Envelopes'', ''The Name of the Star'', ''Truly Devious,'' and ''Suite Scarlett''. Among Johnson's works are collaborative efforts such as ''[[Let It Snow: Three Holiday Romances|Let It Snow]],'' a holiday romance novel of interwoven stories co-written with [[John Green (author)|John Green]] and [[Lauren Myracle]], and a series of novellas found in anthologies ''The Bane Chronicles'', ''Tales from the Shadowhunter Academy'', and ''Ghosts of the Shadow Market.''\n\n==Early life and education==\nJohnson was born in [[Philadelphia]] and attended an all-girl [[Catholicism|Catholic]] preparatory high school. She graduated from the [[University of Delaware]] in 1995 with a degree in English.<ref>http://www1.udel.edu/udmessenger/vol20no1/stories/alumni-johnson-testerman.html</ref> Johnson later worked variously as literary manager of a Philadelphia theater company, a waitress in a theme restaurant, a secretary, a bartender in [[Piccadilly]], and an occasional performer in [[New York City]]. She studied both writing and theatrical dramaturgy at [[Columbia University]], where she received her [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] in Writing.<ref>[http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/about/ Official Bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110325053451/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/about/ |date=March 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Career and writings==\n[[File:(cropped) American authors Lauren Myracle and Maureen Johnson signing at LA Times Festival of Books 2012.png|alt=Johnson, at right, along with fellow author Lauren Myracle at left while signing at the LA Times Festival of Books in 2012.|left|thumb|Johnson, at right, along with fellow author Lauren Myracle at left while signing at the LA Times Festival of Books in 2012.]]\n\n=== First works ===\nJohnson's debut novel ''The Key to the Golden Firebird'' was published in May 2004 by [[HarperCollins|HarperTeen]]. Centered around themes of grief and resilience and set in the suburbs of [[Bucks County, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]] a year after his passing, the novel depicts three sisters of different age as they individually process and come to understand their father's death, and their paths ahead. ''The Key to the Golden Firebird'' entered the market during a resurgence of popular interest in the young adult fiction genre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/6/26/15841216/outsiders-harry-potter-ya-young-adult-se-hinton-jk-rowling|title=The Outsiders reinvented young adult fiction. Harry Potter made it inescapable.|last=Grady|first=Constance|date=2017-06-26|website=Vox|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> In 2005, it received starred reviews from both [[School Library Journal]] and [[Booklist]].\n\nJohnson's second published novel, ''The Bermudez Triangle'' (later reissued as ''On the Count of Three'' in 2013), was released in October 2004. Following three high school seniors who have been best friends since childhood\u2014 Nina, Avery, and Melanie\u2014 two of whom have been dating secretly since the summer, ''The Bermudez Triangle'' explores the complexity of relationships and self-identity, from the changing nature of bonds, to the experiences of both platonic love and attraction, and the gifts and difficulties of first romances. It was selected as a Winter 2004 Book Sense Pick, as well as listed for [[New York Public Library Main Branch|New York Public Library's]] \u201cBooks for the Teen Age 2006\u201d, and the [[American Library Association|American Library Association\u2019s]] Popular Paperbacks for Young Adults, GLTBQ list.\n\nJohnson's third novel and first series, ''[[13 Little Blue Envelopes]]'' was published in August 2005 by HarperTeen. The story follows seventeen-year-old Virginia (Ginny) Blackstone, as she embarks on a journey throughout Europe by following a series of instructions left to her within letters from her beloved, self-proclaimed \"Runaway Aunt\" Peg, upon notice of her passing. While written in the style of contemporary realistic fiction that much of her earlier work is known for, Johnson herself has said she considers Ginny's adventure to be \"a little bit of a fairy tale,\" and has cited the song \"Charmed Life\" by Irish artist Neil Hannon of [[The Divine Comedy (band)|The Divine Comedy]] for its likeness to the spirit with which the novel was written.<ref>{{Citation|title=Maureen Jonhson Interview|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YgymwNeuRmw|language=en|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/podcasts/13_Little_Blue_Envelopes.mp3|title=Wayback Machine|date=2007-10-11|access-date=2019-09-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011114359/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/podcasts/13_Little_Blue_Envelopes.mp3|archive-date=2007-10-11}}</ref> ''The Last Little Blue Envelope'', the sequel to Johnson's 2005 novel, ''[[13 Little Blue Envelopes]]'', was later published in April 2011.<ref>[http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/books/the-last-little-blue-envelope/ The Last Little Blue Envelope] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517144618/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/books/the-last-little-blue-envelope/|date=May 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2006, Johnson's fourth novel ''Devilish'' was published by Razorbill, an imprint of what was then [[Penguin Random House|Penguin Group]]. Set in a [[College-preparatory school|preparatory school]] in [[Rhode Island]] where \"barbed wire keeps the boys out and the ancient nuns keep the girls in,\" ''Devilish'' follows the travails of two senior students, Jane and Allison (Ally), as they experience seemingly supernatural upheavals within their friendship and school year, culminating in what appears to be a battle for Ally's [[soul]]. Marking Johnson's first full departure from contemporary realistic fiction, ''Devilish'' was shortlisted in 2007 for the [[Andre Norton Award]], which celebrates excellence in [[Young adult fiction|YA]] [[science fiction]] and [[fantasy]] novel writing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nebulas.sfwa.org/award-year/2006/|title=2006|last=Fictions|first=\u00a9 2019 Science|last2=America|first2=Fantasy Writers of|website=The Nebula Awards\u00ae|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-29|last3=SFWA\u00ae|first3=Inc|last4=Fiction|first4=Nebula Awards\u00ae are registered trademarks of Science|last5=America|first5=Fantasy Writers of|last6=SFWA|first6=Inc Opinions expressed on this web site are not necessarily those of}}</ref>\n\n=== Series ===\nIn May 2008, Johnson's sixth novel ''Suite Scarlett'' was published by Point. It explores the life of newly fifteen-year-old Scarlett Martin, whose family resides within and personally run the Hopewell hotel. Described as a small \u201cjewel box of a hotel\u201d built at the height of [[Art Deco architecture of New York City|Art Deco]] style in the heart of Manhattan's [[Upper East Side]], the Hopewell is a local institution in need of both repairs and guests. ''Scarlett'' explores family dynamics, coming of age, and some the strange opportunities of [[New York City]] for those who find themselves working in and adjacent to the [[performing arts]]. Upon her fifteenth birthday, as per Martin family tradition, Scarlett is handed the keys to one of their home's suites, as well as the responsibility of maintaining it and seeing after its guests. Scarlett's struggles to meet the eccentric demands of the Empire Suite's first and apparently now permanent tenant, Mrs. Amberson, become the basis of much of the experiences of her formative years. ''Suite Scarlett'' was selected by the American Library Association for their list Best Books for Young Adults 2009, and received a starred review by Booklist.\n\nIn September 2011, Johnson's tenth novel ''The Name of the Star'' was published by Speak. The first of four titles to be set in the ''Shades of London'' series, ''The Name of the Star'' follows Louisiana teenager Rory Deveaux as she travels to London to begin boarding school, where she is quickly pulled into the center of a world of paranormal murders that mimic those of [[Jack the Ripper]].<ref>Citation error. See inline comment how to fix. {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/911002677 by a bug in VisualEditor and later identified by a bot. The original cite can be found at Special:Permalink/910999906 (or in a rev close to it) in either cite #9 or cite #1 - find and verify the cite and replace this template with it (1). [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> In 2012, ''The Name of the Star'' was nominated for an [[Edgar Award]] for excellence in the category of young adult fiction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theedgars.com/nominees.html|title=Edgar Nominees|date=2012-03-07|access-date=2019-08-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307172053/http://www.theedgars.com/nominees.html|archive-date=2012-03-07}}</ref> The second and third ''Shades'' novels, ''The Madness Underneath'' and ''The Shadow Cabinet'', were published in February 2013 and February 2015, respectively.<ref>Citation error. See inline comment how to fix. {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/911002677 by a bug in VisualEditor and later identified by a bot. The original cite can be found at Special:Permalink/910999906 (or in a rev close to it) in either cite #10 or cite #2 - find and verify the cite and replace this template with it (1). [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> A forthcoming novel is confirmed to conclude the series, with a publication date expected to be announced for sometime after January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/1159183340756508672|title=There will be another. It's been a long time coming.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2019-08-07|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, ''[[The Bane Chronicles]]'', an anthology of novellas written with fellow [[young adult fiction]] authors [[Cassandra Clare]] and [[Sarah Rees Brennan]] was first released in hardcover by Margaret K. McElderry Books. Prior to their print release as a collected anthology, each title was initially debuted separately in [[E-book|ebook]] and downloadable audiobook formats. ''The Bane Chronicles'' is set within the same world as Clare's ''The Mortal Instruments'' and ''The Infernal Devices'' series, with the stated intent being to explore the life of the \"enigmatic Magnus Bane,\" a character of Clare's whose \"alluring personality, flamboyant style, and sharp wit...\" had become a favorite among fans.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Bane Chronicles|last=Clare|first=Cassandra|last2=Brennan|first2=Sarah Rees|last3=Johnson|first3=Maureen|publisher=Margaret K. McElderry Books|year=2014|isbn=9781442495999|location=United States|pages=Dedication}}</ref> Johnson's principle contributions to the anthology and their first availability are as follows: ''The Runaway Queen'' (May 2013), ''The Rise of the Hotel Dumort'' (August 2013), ''The Fall of the Hotel Dumort'' (October 2013), and ''The Last Stand of the New York Institute'' (December 2013, co-written with Clare and Sarah Rees Brennan). ''The Bane Chronicles'' has appeared on the New York Times bestsellers list for children's series a number of times, beginning the week of July 7, 2013.\n\n''Truly Devious'' (Katherine Tegen Books, 2018) is the first in a trilogy of mystery novels to follow Stevie Bell, a [[true crime]] aficionado set to begin studies at the exclusive yet ideal-minded Ellingham Academy in the remote mountains of [[Vermont]], where she's prepared to put her mind to one primary goal: solving one of the great unsolved crimes of [[History of the United States|American history]]. The second novel of the trilogy, ''The Vanishing Stair'', was published January 2019. The third and concluding novel, ''The Hand on the Wall'', is scheduled for publication in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/books/2019/06/20/maureen-johnson-truly-devious-finale-preview/|title=Exclusive: Maureen Johnson is wrapping up her Truly Devious trilogy in style|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n=== On the topic of book banning ===\nIn June 2007, the parent of a student in [[Bartlesville, Oklahoma]], challenged ''The Bermudez Triangle''<nowiki/>'s presence within the school. The parent went on record saying \u201cI didn\u2019t appreciate that it was there,\u201d referring to the book being in the library. \u201cI just don\u2019t think homosexual materials belong in our schools.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.is/zLai|title=Examiner Enterprise|date=2012-07-01|website=archive.is|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref> While [[Book censorship|book challenges]] in the [[United States|U.S.]] are not uncommon,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/advocacy/sites/ala.org.advocacy/files/content/banned/bannedbooksweek/ideasandresources/free_downloads/2008banned.pdf|title=Books Challenged or Banned in 2007-2008|last=Doyle|first=Robert|website=American Library Association|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107083729/http://www.ala.org/advocacy/sites/ala.org.advocacy/files/content/banned/bannedbooksweek/ideasandresources/free_downloads/2008banned.pdf|archive-date=2019-01-07|url-status=|access-date=2019-08-30}}</ref> Johnson's response upon learning of the issue was to quickly publish a blog post on her website calling for greater transparency in the school system's challenge process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2007/05/19/im-in-ur-skool-banin-ur-book/|title=Maureen Johnson Books \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb IM IN UR SKOOL BANIN UR BOOK|date=2012-03-28|access-date=2019-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328112502/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2007/05/19/im-in-ur-skool-banin-ur-book/|archive-date=2012-03-28}}</ref> In an attempt to resolve the controversy, the school board did not remove the book but instead placed it in a restricted area of the high school's library.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archive.examiner-enterprise.com/articles/2007/08/09/community/com652.txt |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120708141559/http://archive.examiner-enterprise.com/articles/2007/08/09/community/com652.txt |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 8, 2012 |title=Not Quite Banned Book up for removal remains in Mid-High library on reserve shelf |publisher=Bartlesville Examiner-Enterprise |date=August 9, 2007 |author=Jessica Miller |accessdate=2012-04-23}}</ref> In an interview in January 2008 in retrospect of the situation, Johnson expressed the primary concern that censorship of stories on the basis of a character's identity will adversely effect all children, particularly those who happen to share that given identity. On the school's copy of ''The Bermudez Triangle'' ultimately being placed in a restricted area, Johnson stated: \"To do so is basically saying to the gay kids, 'There\u2019s something dirty about you.' Anyone who would say that is the true filthmonger.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ncac.org/update/krrp-interview-with-author-maureen-johnson|title=KRRP Interview with Author, Maureen Johnson|date=2017-10-31|access-date=2019-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031032723/https://ncac.org/update/krrp-interview-with-author-maureen-johnson|archive-date=2017-10-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Further chronology ===\nIn May 2007, Johnson's novel ''Girl at Sea'' was published by HarperTeen. The novel follows seventeen-year-old Clio Ford's attempts to make the best of being suddenly cast away from her home for the summer in pursuit of a mysterious treasure abroad. Set primarily aboard a pre-owned yacht somewhere amidst the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] at the behest of her father, it explores Clio's perspective as she struggles with first romantic infatuations, dives at sea among shipwrecks, and navigates a series of new relationships and situations.\n\nIn May 2009, Johnson contributed her story \"The Law of Suspects\" to ''Vacations from Hell'', a collection of supernatural tales on the topic of vacations gone awry, along with fellow authors [[Libba Bray]], Cassandra Clare, Claudia Gray, and Sarah Mlynowski.\n\nOn November 27, 2009, Johnson first became a [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' Best Selling author]] when ''Let It Snow: Three Holiday Romances'' (October 2008, Speak) reached number ten on the Children's Paperback list.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/06/books/bestseller/bestchildren.html New York Times Bestselling Children's Books, November 27, 2009]</ref> A holiday romance novel of interwoven stories co-written with [[John Green (author)|John Green]] and [[Lauren Myracle]], ''Let It Snow'' begins with Johnson's \"[[Let It Snow: Three Holiday Romances#The%20Jubilee%20Express|The Jubilee Express]]\".  The book is currently under adaption to film, with distribution by [[Netflix]] set for a November 2019 release.\n\nJohnson worked a scriptwriter for [[Electronic Arts|EA Games]] in 2009, helping develop the Nintendo DS and PSP versions of the [[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (video game)|''Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince'' video game]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/about/|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110325053451/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/about/|archivedate=2011-03-25|url-status=dead|accessdate=2011-02-13}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Johnson's eighth book and the second title in the ''Scarlett'' series, ''Scarlett Fever'', was published. According to Johnson later in June 2014,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/474313033951764480|title=There WILL be a third Scarlett. Thank you for asking.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2014-06-04|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-08-10}} {{verify source|date=September 2019|reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/913296305 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/913275959 cite #10 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> a third entry in the ''Scarlett'' series was well underway, but no further news has been publicly available since then. At the time of her statement, both titles were receiving their first publication within the [[United Kingdom|U.K.]] by Hot Key Books, an imprint of [[Bonnier Group]].\n\nIn September 2010, Johnson contributed her story \"The Children of the Revolution\" to ''Zombies vs. Unicorns'', edited by [[Holly Black]] and [[Justine Larbalestier]]. Each of the twelve stories featured in ''Zombies vs. Unicorns'' aim to make a case for their respective side. Fellow authors in the anthology include Cassandra Clare, Libba Bray, Meg Cabot, Alaya Dawn Johnson, Carrie Ryan, Scott Westerfeld, Garth Nix, Kathleen Duey, Margo Lanagan, Naomi Novik, Diana Peterfreund, and Margo Lanagan.\n\nIn 2011, Johnson became the ongoing lead coordinator of LeakyCon's Lit Track programming, the literary focused experience for fans of young adult fiction more broadly. A production of [[Mischief Management]], LeakyCon is the largest regularly held Harry Potter fan convention in North America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-xpm-2012-08-12-ct-ent-0813-leaky-con-20120812-story.html|title=Harry Potter fans create magic at LeakyCon|last=Borrelli|first=Christopher|date=August 12, 2012|website=The Chicago Tribune|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Topics of the Lit Track have included the importance of supporting diversity within young adult literature, the experience of writing romance fiction that respects teenaged characters, use of critical thinking in examining the labels we ascribe to particular kinds of fiction, and panels discussing the stories that authors of popular fiction first wrote for themselves in their teenage years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://meganmorrison.net/2014/08/leakycon-my-lit-track-experience/|title=LeakyCon! My Lit-Track Experience|last=Morrison|first=Megan|date=August 11, 2014|website=Megan Morrison|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, Johnson was selected to represent the [[Young adult fiction|YA]] category for [[World Book Day (UK and Ireland)|World Book Day]] in the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldbookday.com/2013/09/ultimate-feast-of-literary-fun-awaits-youngsters-with-return-of-largest-annual-childrens-books-celebration/|title=ULTIMATE FEAST OF LITERARY FUN AWAITS YOUNGSTERS WITH RETURN OF LARGEST ANNUAL CHILDREN'S BOOKS CELEBRATION {{!}} World Book Day|date=2014-04-08|access-date=2019-08-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408014718/http://www.worldbookday.com/2013/09/ultimate-feast-of-literary-fun-awaits-youngsters-with-return-of-largest-annual-childrens-books-celebration/|archive-date=2014-04-08}}</ref> with the first publication of her [[novella]] ''The Boy in the Smoke'', a prequel story to the ''Shades of London'' series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wattpad.com/65902491-the-boy-in-the-smoke-a-note-about-this-story|title=THE BOY IN THE SMOKE - A NOTE ABOUT THIS STORY - Wattpad|website=www.wattpad.com|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> That August, ''The Boy in the Smoke'' was additionally released to an international audience for free through the online reading and story writing platform [[Wattpad]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wattpad.com/65902491-the-boy-in-the-smoke-a-note-about-this-story#|title=THE BOY IN THE SMOKE - A NOTE ABOUT THIS STORY - Wattpad|website=www.wattpad.com|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, ''[[Tales From the Shadowhunter Academy|Tales from the Shadowhunter Academy]]'', an anthology of novellas written with fellow popular young adult fiction authors Cassandra Clare, Sarah Rees Brennan, and [[Robin Wasserman]] was first released in hardcover by Margaret K. McElderry Books. Prior to their print release as a collected anthology, each title was initially debuted separately in [[E-book|ebook]] and downloadable audiobook formats. ''Tales from the Shadowhunter Academy'' is described as providing an epilogue to Clare's ''Mortal Instruments'' series, exploring the experiences of Simon Lewis, who now finds himself stripped of his memories and unsure of his identity but determined to figure it out as his journey continues. [[Maureen Johnson#cite%20note-11|[11]]] Johnson's principle contributions and their first availability are the stories ''The Whitechapel Fiend'' (April 2015) and ''The Fiery Trial'' (September 2015).\n\n''How I Resist: Activism and Hope for a New Generation'' (Wednesday Books, 2018) is a collection of essays, songs, illustrations, and interviews on the topics of activism and hope, with all author proceeds donated to support the [[American Civil Liberties Union|ACLU]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.malindalo.com/blog/2018/5/14/how-i-resist-is-out-today|title=HOW I RESIST is out today|last=Lo|first=Malinda|date=May 15, 2018|website=Malinda Lo|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Edited by Johnson, and spurred by her concern for helping young readers navigate how they might respond to the political climate in the [[United States|U.S.]] post the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]], the anthology features thirty artists of diverse experience sets. Contributors include [[Jacqueline Woodson]], [[Malinda Lo]], [[Jason Reynolds]], [[Dana Schwartz]], [[Jodi Picoult]], [[Sabaa Tahir]], Hebh Jamal, [[Javier Mu\u00f1oz (actor)|Javier Mu\u00f1oz]], [[Libba Bray]], John Paul Brammer, and more.  \n\n== Social media presence, advocacy, and activism ==\nJohnson has maintained a personal website about her work and experiences as an author since 2005, with blog entries dating as far back as August of that year. In June 2008, she joined then-new micro-blogging platform [[Twitter]] as one of its early users, where she has likened her many posts about everything from the news of the day to searching the town of [[Guildford]] for a baking pan<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/222769080434831362?s=20|title=Okay. Does anyone in GUILDFORD have a LOAF BAKING TIN? Get in touch at once!|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2012-07-10|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-09-15}}</ref> to the habit she had developed of leaving post-it notes around for others to read while working in theater productions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/authors/profiles/article/56094-maureen-johnson-the-queen-of-teen.html|title=Maureen Johnson: The Queen of Teen|last=|first=|date=|website=www.publishersweekly.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\n=== YA for Obama ===\nIn September 2008, shortly before the general election, Johnson launched the inclusive political social networking community ''YA for Obama'' to support then [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] [[Barack Obama]]'s candidacy for [[President of the United States|President]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://yaforobama.ning.com/profiles/blog/show?id=2246335:BlogPost:1764|title=WHAT IS YA FOR OBAMA? - YA for Obama|date=2009-08-08|access-date=2019-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090808092656/http://yaforobama.ning.com/profiles/blog/show?id=2246335:BlogPost:1764|archive-date=2009-08-08}}</ref><ref>Kellogg, Carolyn (September 24, 2008). [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/jacketcopy/2008/09/authors-of-youn.html \"Authors of young adult novels support Obama\"]. ''[[the Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref> Intended as a way to help organize support and interest for Obama's campaign among young people and provide safe avenues for them to engage the American political process, ''YA for Obama'' used the online community publishing platform [[Ning (website)|Ning]], and comprised discussion forums, user-generated content such as videos and photos, and daily blog updates written by popular [[Young adult fiction|Young Adult fiction]] authors. Notable contributors included [[Judy Blume]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://yaforobama.ning.com/profiles/blog/show?id=2246335:BlogPost:1396|title=Why I Support Obama by Judy Blume - YA for Obama|date=2008-12-31|access-date=2019-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231211342/http://yaforobama.ning.com/profiles/blog/show?id=2246335:BlogPost:1396|archive-date=2008-12-31}}</ref> [[Scott Westerfeld]], [[Lauren Myracle]], [[Cecily von Ziegesar]], and [[Megan McCafferty]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://yaforobama.ning.com/profiles/blog/show?id=2246335%3ABlogPost%3A13877|title=How to Persuade Your Parents to Vote For Obama by Megan McCafferty - YA for Obama|date=2008-12-11|access-date=2019-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211214118/http://yaforobama.ning.com/profiles/blog/show?id=2246335%3ABlogPost%3A13877|archive-date=2008-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://yaforobama.ning.com/|title=YA for Obama|date=2009-04-20|access-date=2019-02-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328130900/http://yaforobama.ning.com/|archive-date=2010-03-28}}</ref>\n\n=== ShelterBox ===\nIn February 2011, in response to the [[2011 Christchurch earthquake|earthquake in Christchurch]], New Zealand, Johnson took to Twitter in an effort to raise funds for [[ShelterBox]], an international disaster relief charity established in 2000 in Helston, Cornwall, UK, that provides emergency shelter and other aid items to families around the world who have lost their homes to disaster or conflict.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/02/23/the-last-little-shelterbox/|title=Maureen Johnson Books \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb THE LAST LITTLE SHELTERBOX|date=2011-02-26|access-date=2019-09-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110226103102/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/02/23/the-last-little-shelterbox/|archive-date=2011-02-26}}</ref> A ShelterBox (the actual aid kit itself) is designed to provide families with stable, lasting shelter and a level of independence after a disaster, and include high quality aid items chosen to best suit to the particular situation at hand. As described by Johnson at the time:<blockquote>''When there\u2019s a disaster, Shelterbox deploys trained volunteers (hardcore people who\u2019ve done survival training) with their special shelters in a box. The kits vary, but all contain the basic life-sustaining materials people need to survive after a disaster. Tents that fit families of ten. Blankets. A stove. Tools. You can get a good look at the kits here. Use your mouse to examine the various contents. Each box costs \u00a3590 (about $950) and literally puts a roof over someone\u2019s head.''</blockquote>Funds were raised through a general call to action and the giving away of signed ARCs (advance reader copies of books) and other literary materials to donors. The prizes themselves were donated by various authors in support of the aid effort. Donors were asked to make contributions to the charity directly, while sharing a common label so that their total as a group could be tracked. The amount raised was $15,202 USD, enough to fund 16 shelters and supplies.\n\nWeeks later, when the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]] occurred, Johnson returned to Twitter with fellow authors to attempt to replicate the aid that was raised, this time with the people of Japan and anyone directly affected by the earthquake and tsunami in mind.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/03/11/shelterbox-in-japan/|title=Maureen Johnson Books \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb SHELTERBOX IN JAPAN|date=2011-03-15|access-date=2019-09-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315022449/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/03/11/shelterbox-in-japan/|archive-date=2011-03-15}}</ref> Almost the same amount of money was raised, totaling $14,202 USD<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/03/13/shelterbox-in-japan-the-results/|title=Maureen Johnson Books \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb SHELTERBOX IN JAPAN: THE RESULTS!|date=2012-03-20|access-date=2019-09-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320184711/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/03/13/shelterbox-in-japan-the-results/|archive-date=2012-03-20}}</ref>, enough for an additional 14 shelter kits to be deployed to those who needed them.\n\nIn May, in response to the [[2011 Joplin tornado|tornado in Joplin, Missouri]], Johnson and fellow authors used the same strategy to raise an additional $4,913.90 USD, with funds split between ShelterBox and the [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/05/23/shelter-for-joplin/|title=Maureen Johnson Books \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb SHELTER FOR JOPLIN|date=2013-05-14|access-date=2019-09-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514021753/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/05/23/shelter-for-joplin/|archive-date=2013-05-14}}</ref>\n\nJohnson has continued to advocate publicly via social media for awareness on behalf of ShelterBox at times of disaster and particular need.\n\n== Other creative projects ==\n\n=== VlogBrothers ===\nIn January 2010, Johnson was acknowledged as [[John Green (author)|John Green]]'s ''secret sister'' on the popular [[YouTube]] channel [[Vlogbrothers|VlogBrothers]]. With the reveal of this honorary title, Johnson took on the role of creating videos for the channel during his absence to paternity leave. Johnson later reprised the duty after the birth of Green's second child in 2013.\n\n=== Welcome to Night Vale ===\nSince June 2014, Johnson has voiced the character Intern Maureen on the surreal fiction podcast ''[[Welcome to Night Vale]]'', as well as occasionally performed the character live on stage. In June 2016, while in conversation at [[92nd Street Y|92Y]] in New York, co-creator Joseph Fink explained that the character of Intern Maureen was initially written in the image of Johnson, but quickly killed off, as death is a kind of tradition for most interns of the Night Vale Radio station. Johnson, a vocal fan<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/368933183032528896|title=Now that I've found @NightValeRadio, I don't need superfluities, like scuba, or wifi, or food, or clothes. Night Vale takes care of me.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2013-08-17|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-08-13}}</ref> of the podcast, in turn led a Twitter campaign in protest, leading Fink and Cranor to agree to bring the character back on the condition that Johnson perform the role herself. Intern Maureen's continued survival has since become an ongoing joke within the stories. Johnson provided the foreword for ''The Great Glowing Coils of the Universe'' (Harper Perennial, 2016), a collected volume of early podcast scripts.\n\n=== Says Who? ===\nIn September 2016, Johnson began co-hosting the podcast ''[http://www.sayswhopodcast.com Says Who?]'' alongside former [[Punk Planet]] editor and author Dan Sinker. Self-described as a coping strategy, ''Says Who?'' was originally conceived as an eight-week project in which Johnson and Sinker would talk with political experts about how they were surviving news coverage of the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 Presidential Election]]. The podcast has since continued past the results of the election, and switched to a biweekly format in which the hosts attempt to humorously discuss the news of the day, and more personally, share how they are coping as citizens in the current political era.\n\n==Personal life==\nJohnson lives in New York City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/1023306629058637825|title=I have lived in NYC since 1997!|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2018-07-28|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> A self-described [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]] since 1994, she has frequently shared her love for both vegan and vegetarian cooking through blog posts and tweets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/38423732288491520|title=\"@sundust When did you become a vegetarian, and why?\" In 1994, and FOR MANY REASONS.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2011-02-17|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> \"I'm a vegetarian from Philadelphia, which means I spend my life trying to make a vegetarian steak sandwich.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/1023306178967887877|title=I'm a vegetarian from Philadelphia, which means I spend my life trying to make a vegetarian steak sandwich.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2018-07-28|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nOn June 23, 2018, Johnson was married in New York's [[Central Park]] at the [[The Ramble and Lake|Ladies Pavilion]]. The reception was held shortly thereafter at [[Housing Works]], a non-profit bookstore and venue space whose mission is to end the dual crises of [[homelessness]] and [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/1011314860884418562|title=So when I get the photos I hope to take you on a tour of this MAGICAL OCCASION which was really just perfect. We were married in Central Park, at the Ladies Pavilion, surrounded by friends and family. Then we took off and walked ALL THROUGH THE PARK.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2018-06-25|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> Reflecting upon the experience on Twitter, she wrote \"There was no better place to have a party on Pride weekend.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/1011315147191746564?s=20|title=Thank you to so many people for making it all happen. Thank you to @HousingWorksBks. There was no better place to have a party on Pride weekend. Thank you to @DaphneUn and @herzwesten. And thank YOU, dear Reader.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2018-06-25|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Standalone novels===\n\n*''[[The Key to the Golden Firebird|The Key to the Golden Firebird]]'' (May 25, 2004)\n*''The Bermudez Triangle'' (October 7, 2004), later reissued in America as ''On the Count of Three'' (April 18, 2013)\n*''Devilish'' (September 7, 2006)\n*''Girl at Sea'' (May 29, 2007)\n*''[[Let It Snow: Three Holiday Romances|Let It Snow: Three Holiday Romances]]'' (Co-written with [[John Green (author)|John Green]] and [[Lauren Myracle]]) (October 2, 2008)\n\n===Series novels===\n\n====13 Little Blue Envelopes====\n\n*''[[13 Little Blue Envelopes|13 Little Blue Envelopes]]'' (August 23, 2005)\n*''The Last Little Blue Envelope'' (April 26, 2011)\n\n====Suite Scarlett====\n\n*''Suite Scarlett'' (May 1, 2008)\n*''Scarlett Fever'' (February 1, 2010)\n\n====Shades of London====\n\n*''The Name of the Star'' (September 29, 2011)\n*''The Madness Underneath'' (February 26, 2013)\n* ''The Boy in the Smoke ''(Prequel novella for World Book Day) (February 24, 2014)\n* ''The Shadow Cabinet'' (February 10, 2015)\n\n====Truly Devious====\n\n*''Truly Devious'' (January 16, 2018)\n*''The Vanishing Stair'' (January 22, 2019)\n*''The Hand on the Wall'' (January 21, 2020)\n\n===Anthologized novellas===\n\n==== The Bane Chronicles ====\nCo-written with [[Cassandra Clare]] & [[Sarah Rees Brennan]] \n*''The Runaway Queen'' (May 21, 2013)\n*''The Rise of the Hotel Dumort'' (August 20, 2013)\n*''The Fall of the Hotel Dumort'' (October 15, 2013)\n*''The Last Stand of the New York Institute'' (December 17, 2013)\n*''The Bane Chronicles'' (Compiled print edition - November 11, 2014)\n\n====Tales from the Shadowhunter Academy====\nCo-written with [[Cassandra Clare]], [[Sarah Rees Brennan]] & [[Robin Wasserman]] \n*''The Whitechapel Fiend'' (April 21, 2015)\n*''The Fiery Trial'' (September 22, 2015)\n*''Tales from the Shadowhunter Academy'' (Compiled print edition - November 15, 2016)\n\n====Ghosts of the Shadow Market: An Anthology of Tales====\nCo-written with [[Cassandra Clare]], [[Sarah Rees Brennan]], [[Kelly Link]] & [[Robin Wasserman]]\n\n*''Every Exquisite Thing'' (June 12, 2018)\n*''A Deeper Love'' (August 14, 2018)\n*''Ghosts of the Shadow Market: An Anthology of Tales'' (Compiled print edition - June 4, 2019)\n\n===Other publications===\n==== Anthologies edited ====\n* ''How I Resist: Activism and Hope for a New Generation'' (May 15, 2018)\n\n==== Short stories ====\n*\"The Law of Suspects\" in ''Vacations From Hell'' (May 26, 2009)\n*\"The Children of the Revolution\" in ''Zombies vs. Unicorns'' (September 21, 2010)\n\n====Essays====\n*\"Hot Sex and Horrific Parenting in His Dark Materials\" in ''The World of the Golden Compass'' (January 28, 2007)\n*\"Stupid Monsters and Child Surgeons\" in ''Life Inside My Mind: 31 Authors Share Their Personal Struggles'' (April 10, 2018)\n\n==== Short works in support of the Harry Potter Alliance (e-book only) ====\n\n* \"1776: A Story in Tweets\" first released to donors of the HPA's Equality FTW campaign (September 9, 2012)\n* \"A Study in Sink\" first released to donors of the HPA's Equality FTW 2013 campaign (February 11, 2014)\n* \"The Sign of Tree\" first released to donors of the HPA's Equality FTW 2014 campaign (February 20, 2015)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n*<big>''13 Little Blue Envelopes'' - [[American Library Association|ALA]] Teens' Top Ten 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/ala/yalsa/teenreading/teenstopten/06ttt.cfm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-05-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080525131847/http://www.ala.org/ala/yalsa/teenreading/teenstopten/06ttt.cfm |archivedate=2008-05-25 }}</ref></big>\n*<big>''Devilish'' - 2007 [[Andre Norton Award]] nomination<ref>http://www.sfawardswatch.com/?page_id=72</ref></big>\n*<big>\"Most Interesting Twitter User to Follow\" [[Mashable]] Open Web Awards 2009<ref>http://mashable.com/2009/12/16/open-web-awards-2009-50-winners/</ref></big>\n*<big>Ranked as number 15 of TIME's \"The 140 Best Twitter Feeds of 2011\"</big><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2058946_2060626,00.html|title=The 140 Best Twitter Feeds of 2011 - TIME|date=2011-03-28|work=Time|access-date=2019-09-15|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref>\n*<big>''The Name of the Star'' - [[YALSA]] 2012 Best Fiction for Young Adults<ref>http://www.ala.org/yalsa/bfya/2012</ref></big>\n*<big>''The Name of the Star'' - [[Edgar Award]] nomination for excellence in [[Young adult fiction|Young Adult fiction]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theedgars.com/nominees.html|title=Edgar Nominees|date=2012-03-07|access-date=2019-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307172053/http://www.theedgars.com/nominees.html|archive-date=2012-03-07}}</ref></big>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Maureen Johnson}}\n*{{official website|http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com}}\n*[https://lccn.loc.gov/n2003054816 Maureen Johnson] at [[Library of Congress]] Authorities\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080622121816/http://www.thisispoint.com/authors/maureenjohnson.asp Scholastic Point author bio]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Maureen}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:American young adult novelists]]\n[[Category:Columbia University School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:University of Delaware alumni]]\n[[Category:Women writers of young adult literature]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American women podcasters]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:Internet activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian writer and voice actress}}\n{{about|the author|the character from ''Rent''|Rent (musical)#Maureen Johnson|character by Robert A. Heinlein|Maureen Johnson (Heinlein character)}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image = American author Maureen Johnson at LA Times Festival of Books 2012.png\n| imagesize = \n| name = Maureen Johnson\n| pseudonym = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1973|02|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania, United States\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = Novelist\n| nationality = United States\n| period = 2004\u2013present\n| genre = [[Young adult literature|Young adult fiction]], [[Mystery fiction]]\n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| signature  = a maureen johnson signature.svg\n| website = {{URL|http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com}}\n}}\n'''Maureen Johnson''' (born February 16, 1973) is an American author of [[Young adult literature|young adult fiction]]. Her published novels include ''13 Little Blue Envelopes'', ''The Name of the Star'', ''Truly Devious,'' and ''Suite Scarlett''. Among Johnson's works are collaborative efforts such as ''[[Let It Snow: Three Holiday Romances|Let It Snow]],'' a holiday romance novel of interwoven stories co-written with [[John Green (author)|John Green]] and [[Lauren Myracle]], and a series of novellas found in anthologies ''The Bane Chronicles'', ''Tales from the Shadowhunter Academy'', and ''Ghosts of the Shadow Market.''\n\n==Early life and education==\nJohnson was born in [[Philadelphia]] and attended an all-girl [[Catholicism|Catholic]] preparatory high school. She graduated from the [[University of Delaware]] in 1995 with a degree in English.<ref>http://www1.udel.edu/udmessenger/vol20no1/stories/alumni-johnson-testerman.html</ref> Johnson later worked variously as literary manager of a Philadelphia theater company, a waitress in a theme restaurant, a secretary, a bartender in [[Piccadilly]], and an occasional performer in [[New York City]]. She studied both writing and theatrical dramaturgy at [[Columbia University]], where she received her [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] in Writing.<ref>[http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/about/ Official Bio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110325053451/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/about/ |date=March 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Career and writings==\n[[File:(cropped) American authors Lauren Myracle and Maureen Johnson signing at LA Times Festival of Books 2012.png|alt=Johnson, at right, along with fellow author Lauren Myracle at left while signing at the LA Times Festival of Books in 2012.|left|thumb|Johnson, at right, along with fellow author Lauren Myracle at left while signing at the LA Times Festival of Books in 2012.]]\n\n=== First works ===\nJohnson's debut novel ''The Key to the Golden Firebird'' was published in May 2004 by [[HarperCollins|HarperTeen]]. Centered around themes of grief and resilience and set in the suburbs of [[Bucks County, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]] a year after his passing, the novel depicts three sisters of different age as they individually process and come to understand their father's death, and their paths ahead. ''The Key to the Golden Firebird'' entered the market during a resurgence of popular interest in the young adult fiction genre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/6/26/15841216/outsiders-harry-potter-ya-young-adult-se-hinton-jk-rowling|title=The Outsiders reinvented young adult fiction. Harry Potter made it inescapable.|last=Grady|first=Constance|date=2017-06-26|website=Vox|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> In 2005, it received starred reviews from both [[School Library Journal]] and [[Booklist]].\n\nJohnson's second published novel, ''The Bermudez Triangle'' (later reissued as ''On the Count of Three'' in 2013), was released in October 2004. Following three high school seniors who have been best friends since childhood\u2014 Nina, Avery, and Melanie\u2014 two of whom have been dating secretly since the summer, ''The Bermudez Triangle'' explores the complexity of relationships and self-identity, from the changing nature of bonds, to the experiences of both platonic love and attraction, and the gifts and difficulties of first romances. It was selected as a Winter 2004 Book Sense Pick, as well as listed for [[New York Public Library Main Branch|New York Public Library's]] \u201cBooks for the Teen Age 2006\u201d, and the [[American Library Association|American Library Association\u2019s]] Popular Paperbacks for Young Adults, GLTBQ list.\n\nJohnson's third novel and first series, ''[[13 Little Blue Envelopes]]'' was published in August 2005 by HarperTeen. The story follows seventeen-year-old Virginia (Ginny) Blackstone, as she embarks on a journey throughout Europe by following a series of instructions left to her within letters from her beloved, self-proclaimed \"Runaway Aunt\" Peg, upon notice of her passing. While written in the style of contemporary realistic fiction that much of her earlier work is known for, Johnson herself has said she considers Ginny's adventure to be \"a little bit of a fairy tale,\" and has cited the song \"Charmed Life\" by Irish artist Neil Hannon of [[The Divine Comedy (band)|The Divine Comedy]] for its likeness to the spirit with which the novel was written.<ref>{{Citation|title=Maureen Jonhson Interview|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YgymwNeuRmw|language=en|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/podcasts/13_Little_Blue_Envelopes.mp3|title=Wayback Machine|date=2007-10-11|access-date=2019-09-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011114359/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/podcasts/13_Little_Blue_Envelopes.mp3|archive-date=2007-10-11}}</ref> ''The Last Little Blue Envelope'', the sequel to Johnson's 2005 novel, ''[[13 Little Blue Envelopes]]'', was later published in April 2011.<ref>[http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/books/the-last-little-blue-envelope/ The Last Little Blue Envelope] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517144618/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/books/the-last-little-blue-envelope/|date=May 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2006, Johnson's fourth novel ''Devilish'' was published by Razorbill, an imprint of what was then [[Penguin Random House|Penguin Group]]. Set in a [[College-preparatory school|preparatory school]] in [[Rhode Island]] where \"barbed wire keeps the boys out and the ancient nuns keep the girls in,\" ''Devilish'' follows the travails of two senior students, Jane and Allison (Ally), as they experience seemingly supernatural upheavals within their friendship and school year, culminating in what appears to be a battle for Ally's [[soul]]. Marking Johnson's first full departure from contemporary realistic fiction, ''Devilish'' was shortlisted in 2007 for the [[Andre Norton Award]], which celebrates excellence in [[Young adult fiction|YA]] [[science fiction]] and [[fantasy]] novel writing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nebulas.sfwa.org/award-year/2006/|title=2006|last=Fictions|first=\u00a9 2019 Science|last2=America|first2=Fantasy Writers of|website=The Nebula Awards\u00ae|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-29|last3=SFWA\u00ae|first3=Inc|last4=Fiction|first4=Nebula Awards\u00ae are registered trademarks of Science|last5=America|first5=Fantasy Writers of|last6=SFWA|first6=Inc Opinions expressed on this web site are not necessarily those of}}</ref>\n\n=== Series ===\nIn May 2008, Johnson's sixth novel ''Suite Scarlett'' was published by Point. It explores the life of newly fifteen-year-old Scarlett Martin, whose family resides within and personally run the Hopewell hotel. Described as a small \u201cjewel box of a hotel\u201d built at the height of [[Art Deco architecture of New York City|Art Deco]] style in the heart of Manhattan's [[Upper East Side]], the Hopewell is a local institution in need of both repairs and guests. ''Scarlett'' explores family dynamics, coming of age, and some the strange opportunities of [[New York City]] for those who find themselves working in and adjacent to the [[performing arts]]. Upon her fifteenth birthday, as per Martin family tradition, Scarlett is handed the keys to one of their home's suites, as well as the responsibility of maintaining it and seeing after its guests. Scarlett's struggles to meet the eccentric demands of the Empire Suite's first and apparently now permanent tenant, Mrs. Amberson, become the basis of much of the experiences of her formative years. ''Suite Scarlett'' was selected by the American Library Association for their list Best Books for Young Adults 2009, and received a starred review by Booklist.\n\nIn September 2011, Johnson's tenth novel ''The Name of the Star'' was published by Speak. The first of four titles to be set in the ''Shades of London'' series, ''The Name of the Star'' follows Louisiana teenager Rory Deveaux as she travels to London to begin boarding school, where she is quickly pulled into the center of a world of paranormal murders that mimic those of [[Jack the Ripper]].<ref>Citation error. See inline comment how to fix. {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/911002677 by a bug in VisualEditor and later identified by a bot. The original cite can be found at Special:Permalink/910999906 (or in a rev close to it) in either cite #9 or cite #1 - find and verify the cite and replace this template with it (1). [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> In 2012, ''The Name of the Star'' was nominated for an [[Edgar Award]] for excellence in the category of young adult fiction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theedgars.com/nominees.html|title=Edgar Nominees|date=2012-03-07|access-date=2019-08-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307172053/http://www.theedgars.com/nominees.html|archive-date=2012-03-07}}</ref> The second and third ''Shades'' novels, ''The Madness Underneath'' and ''The Shadow Cabinet'', were published in February 2013 and February 2015, respectively.<ref>Citation error. See inline comment how to fix. {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/911002677 by a bug in VisualEditor and later identified by a bot. The original cite can be found at Special:Permalink/910999906 (or in a rev close to it) in either cite #10 or cite #2 - find and verify the cite and replace this template with it (1). [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> A forthcoming novel is confirmed to conclude the series, with a publication date expected to be announced for sometime after January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/1159183340756508672|title=There will be another. It's been a long time coming.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2019-08-07|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, ''[[The Bane Chronicles]]'', an anthology of novellas written with fellow [[young adult fiction]] authors [[Cassandra Clare]] and [[Sarah Rees Brennan]] was first released in hardcover by Margaret K. McElderry Books. Prior to their print release as a collected anthology, each title was initially debuted separately in [[E-book|ebook]] and downloadable audiobook formats. ''The Bane Chronicles'' is set within the same world as Clare's ''The Mortal Instruments'' and ''The Infernal Devices'' series, with the stated intent being to explore the life of the \"enigmatic Magnus Bane,\" a character of Clare's whose \"alluring personality, flamboyant style, and sharp wit...\" had become a favorite among fans.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Bane Chronicles|last=Clare|first=Cassandra|last2=Brennan|first2=Sarah Rees|last3=Johnson|first3=Maureen|publisher=Margaret K. McElderry Books|year=2014|isbn=9781442495999|location=United States|pages=Dedication}}</ref> Johnson's principle contributions to the anthology and their first availability are as follows: ''The Runaway Queen'' (May 2013), ''The Rise of the Hotel Dumort'' (August 2013), ''The Fall of the Hotel Dumort'' (October 2013), and ''The Last Stand of the New York Institute'' (December 2013, co-written with Clare and Sarah Rees Brennan). ''The Bane Chronicles'' has appeared on the New York Times bestsellers list for children's series a number of times, beginning the week of July 7, 2013.\n\n''Truly Devious'' (Katherine Tegen Books, 2018) is the first in a trilogy of mystery novels to follow Stevie Bell, a [[true crime]] aficionado set to begin studies at the exclusive yet ideal-minded Ellingham Academy in the remote mountains of [[Vermont]], where she's prepared to put her mind to one primary goal: solving one of the great unsolved crimes of [[History of the United States|American history]]. The second novel of the trilogy, ''The Vanishing Stair'', was published January 2019. The third and concluding novel, ''The Hand on the Wall'', is scheduled for publication in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/books/2019/06/20/maureen-johnson-truly-devious-finale-preview/|title=Exclusive: Maureen Johnson is wrapping up her Truly Devious trilogy in style|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n=== On the topic of book banning ===\nIn June 2007, the parent of a student in [[Bartlesville, Oklahoma]], challenged ''The Bermudez Triangle''<nowiki/>'s presence within the school. The parent went on record saying \u201cI didn\u2019t appreciate that it was there,\u201d referring to the book being in the library. \u201cI just don\u2019t think homosexual materials belong in our schools.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.is/zLai|title=Examiner Enterprise|date=2012-07-01|website=archive.is|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref> While [[Book censorship|book challenges]] in the [[United States|U.S.]] are not uncommon,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/advocacy/sites/ala.org.advocacy/files/content/banned/bannedbooksweek/ideasandresources/free_downloads/2008banned.pdf|title=Books Challenged or Banned in 2007-2008|last=Doyle|first=Robert|website=American Library Association|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107083729/http://www.ala.org/advocacy/sites/ala.org.advocacy/files/content/banned/bannedbooksweek/ideasandresources/free_downloads/2008banned.pdf|archive-date=2019-01-07|url-status=|access-date=2019-08-30}}</ref> Johnson's response upon learning of the issue was to quickly publish a blog post on her website calling for greater transparency in the school system's challenge process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2007/05/19/im-in-ur-skool-banin-ur-book/|title=Maureen Johnson Books \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb IM IN UR SKOOL BANIN UR BOOK|date=2012-03-28|access-date=2019-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328112502/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2007/05/19/im-in-ur-skool-banin-ur-book/|archive-date=2012-03-28}}</ref> In an attempt to resolve the controversy, the school board did not remove the book but instead placed it in a restricted area of the high school's library.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archive.examiner-enterprise.com/articles/2007/08/09/community/com652.txt |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120708141559/http://archive.examiner-enterprise.com/articles/2007/08/09/community/com652.txt |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 8, 2012 |title=Not Quite Banned Book up for removal remains in Mid-High library on reserve shelf |publisher=Bartlesville Examiner-Enterprise |date=August 9, 2007 |author=Jessica Miller |accessdate=2012-04-23}}</ref> In an interview in January 2008 in retrospect of the situation, Johnson expressed the primary concern that censorship of stories on the basis of a character's identity will adversely effect all children, particularly those who happen to share that given identity. On the school's copy of ''The Bermudez Triangle'' ultimately being placed in a restricted area, Johnson stated: \"To do so is basically saying to the gay kids, 'There\u2019s something dirty about you.' Anyone who would say that is the true filthmonger.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ncac.org/update/krrp-interview-with-author-maureen-johnson|title=KRRP Interview with Author, Maureen Johnson|date=2017-10-31|access-date=2019-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031032723/https://ncac.org/update/krrp-interview-with-author-maureen-johnson|archive-date=2017-10-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Further chronology ===\nIn May 2007, Johnson's novel ''Girl at Sea'' was published by HarperTeen. The novel follows seventeen-year-old Clio Ford's attempts to make the best of being suddenly cast away from her home for the summer in pursuit of a mysterious treasure abroad. Set primarily aboard a pre-owned yacht somewhere amidst the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] at the behest of her father, it explores Clio's perspective as she struggles with first romantic infatuations, dives at sea among shipwrecks, and navigates a series of new relationships and situations.\n\nIn May 2009, Johnson contributed her story \"The Law of Suspects\" to ''Vacations from Hell'', a collection of supernatural tales on the topic of vacations gone awry, along with fellow authors [[Libba Bray]], Cassandra Clare, Claudia Gray, and Sarah Mlynowski.\n\nOn November 27, 2009, Johnson first became a [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' Best Selling author]] when ''Let It Snow: Three Holiday Romances'' (October 2008, Speak) reached number ten on the Children's Paperback list.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/06/books/bestseller/bestchildren.html New York Times Bestselling Children's Books, November 27, 2009]</ref> A holiday romance novel of interwoven stories co-written with [[John Green (author)|John Green]] and [[Lauren Myracle]], ''Let It Snow'' begins with Johnson's \"[[Let It Snow: Three Holiday Romances#The%20Jubilee%20Express|The Jubilee Express]]\".  The book is currently under adaption to film, with distribution by [[Netflix]] set for a November 2019 release.\n\nJohnson worked a scriptwriter for [[Electronic Arts|EA Games]] in 2009, helping develop the Nintendo DS and PSP versions of the [[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (video game)|''Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince'' video game]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/about/|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110325053451/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/about/|archivedate=2011-03-25|url-status=dead|accessdate=2011-02-13}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Johnson's eighth book and the second title in the ''Scarlett'' series, ''Scarlett Fever'', was published. According to Johnson later in June 2014,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/474313033951764480|title=There WILL be a third Scarlett. Thank you for asking.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2014-06-04|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-08-10}} {{verify source|date=September 2019|reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/913296305 by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite located at Special:Permalink/913275959 cite #10 - verify the cite is accurate and delete this template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> a third entry in the ''Scarlett'' series was well underway, but no further news has been publicly available since then. At the time of her statement, both titles were receiving their first publication within the [[United Kingdom|U.K.]] by Hot Key Books, an imprint of [[Bonnier Group]].\n\nIn September 2010, Johnson contributed her story \"The Children of the Revolution\" to ''Zombies vs. Unicorns'', edited by [[Holly Black]] and [[Justine Larbalestier]]. Each of the twelve stories featured in ''Zombies vs. Unicorns'' aim to make a case for their respective side. Fellow authors in the anthology include Cassandra Clare, Libba Bray, Meg Cabot, Alaya Dawn Johnson, Carrie Ryan, Scott Westerfeld, Garth Nix, Kathleen Duey, Margo Lanagan, Naomi Novik, Diana Peterfreund, and Margo Lanagan.\n\nIn 2011, Johnson became the ongoing lead coordinator of LeakyCon's Lit Track programming, the literary focused experience for fans of young adult fiction more broadly. A production of [[Mischief Management]], LeakyCon is the largest regularly held Harry Potter fan convention in North America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-xpm-2012-08-12-ct-ent-0813-leaky-con-20120812-story.html|title=Harry Potter fans create magic at LeakyCon|last=Borrelli|first=Christopher|date=August 12, 2012|website=The Chicago Tribune|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Topics of the Lit Track have included the importance of supporting diversity within young adult literature, the experience of writing romance fiction that respects teenaged characters, use of critical thinking in examining the labels we ascribe to particular kinds of fiction, and panels discussing the stories that authors of popular fiction first wrote for themselves in their teenage years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://meganmorrison.net/2014/08/leakycon-my-lit-track-experience/|title=LeakyCon! My Lit-Track Experience|last=Morrison|first=Megan|date=August 11, 2014|website=Megan Morrison|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, Johnson was selected to represent the [[Young adult fiction|YA]] category for [[World Book Day (UK and Ireland)|World Book Day]] in the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldbookday.com/2013/09/ultimate-feast-of-literary-fun-awaits-youngsters-with-return-of-largest-annual-childrens-books-celebration/|title=ULTIMATE FEAST OF LITERARY FUN AWAITS YOUNGSTERS WITH RETURN OF LARGEST ANNUAL CHILDREN'S BOOKS CELEBRATION {{!}} World Book Day|date=2014-04-08|access-date=2019-08-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408014718/http://www.worldbookday.com/2013/09/ultimate-feast-of-literary-fun-awaits-youngsters-with-return-of-largest-annual-childrens-books-celebration/|archive-date=2014-04-08}}</ref> with the first publication of her [[novella]] ''The Boy in the Smoke'', a prequel story to the ''Shades of London'' series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wattpad.com/65902491-the-boy-in-the-smoke-a-note-about-this-story|title=THE BOY IN THE SMOKE - A NOTE ABOUT THIS STORY - Wattpad|website=www.wattpad.com|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> That August, ''The Boy in the Smoke'' was additionally released to an international audience for free through the online reading and story writing platform [[Wattpad]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wattpad.com/65902491-the-boy-in-the-smoke-a-note-about-this-story#|title=THE BOY IN THE SMOKE - A NOTE ABOUT THIS STORY - Wattpad|website=www.wattpad.com|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, ''[[Tales From the Shadowhunter Academy|Tales from the Shadowhunter Academy]]'', an anthology of novellas written with fellow popular young adult fiction authors Cassandra Clare, Sarah Rees Brennan, and [[Robin Wasserman]] was first released in hardcover by Margaret K. McElderry Books. Prior to their print release as a collected anthology, each title was initially debuted separately in [[E-book|ebook]] and downloadable audiobook formats. ''Tales from the Shadowhunter Academy'' is described as providing an epilogue to Clare's ''Mortal Instruments'' series, exploring the experiences of Simon Lewis, who now finds himself stripped of his memories and unsure of his identity but determined to figure it out as his journey continues. [[Maureen Johnson#cite%20note-11|[11]]] Johnson's principle contributions and their first availability are the stories ''The Whitechapel Fiend'' (April 2015) and ''The Fiery Trial'' (September 2015).\n\n''How I Resist: Activism and Hope for a New Generation'' (Wednesday Books, 2018) is a collection of essays, songs, illustrations, and interviews on the topics of activism and hope, with all author proceeds donated to support the [[American Civil Liberties Union|ACLU]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.malindalo.com/blog/2018/5/14/how-i-resist-is-out-today|title=HOW I RESIST is out today|last=Lo|first=Malinda|date=May 15, 2018|website=Malinda Lo|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Edited by Johnson, and spurred by her concern for helping young readers navigate how they might respond to the political climate in the [[United States|U.S.]] post the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]], the anthology features thirty artists of diverse experience sets. Contributors include [[Jacqueline Woodson]], [[Malinda Lo]], [[Jason Reynolds]], [[Dana Schwartz]], [[Jodi Picoult]], [[Sabaa Tahir]], Hebh Jamal, [[Javier Mu\u00f1oz (actor)|Javier Mu\u00f1oz]], [[Libba Bray]], John Paul Brammer, and more.  \n\n== Social media presence, advocacy, and activism ==\nJohnson has maintained a personal website about her work and experiences as an author since 2005, with blog entries dating as far back as August of that year. In June 2008, she joined then-new micro-blogging platform [[Twitter]] as one of its early users, where she has likened her many posts about everything from the news of the day to searching the town of [[Guildford]] for a baking pan<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/222769080434831362?s=20|title=Okay. Does anyone in GUILDFORD have a LOAF BAKING TIN? Get in touch at once!|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2012-07-10|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-09-15}}</ref> to the habit she had developed of leaving post-it notes around for others to read while working in theater productions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/authors/profiles/article/56094-maureen-johnson-the-queen-of-teen.html|title=Maureen Johnson: The Queen of Teen|last=|first=|date=|website=www.publishersweekly.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\n=== YA for Obama ===\nIn September 2008, shortly before the general election, Johnson launched the inclusive political social networking community ''YA for Obama'' to support then [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] [[Barack Obama]]'s candidacy for [[President of the United States|President]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://yaforobama.ning.com/profiles/blog/show?id=2246335:BlogPost:1764|title=WHAT IS YA FOR OBAMA? - YA for Obama|date=2009-08-08|access-date=2019-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090808092656/http://yaforobama.ning.com/profiles/blog/show?id=2246335:BlogPost:1764|archive-date=2009-08-08}}</ref><ref>Kellogg, Carolyn (September 24, 2008). [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/jacketcopy/2008/09/authors-of-youn.html \"Authors of young adult novels support Obama\"]. ''[[the Los Angeles Times]]''.</ref> Intended as a way to help organize support and interest for Obama's campaign among young people and provide safe avenues for them to engage the American political process, ''YA for Obama'' used the online community publishing platform [[Ning (website)|Ning]], and comprised discussion forums, user-generated content such as videos and photos, and daily blog updates written by popular [[Young adult fiction|Young Adult fiction]] authors. Notable contributors included [[Judy Blume]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://yaforobama.ning.com/profiles/blog/show?id=2246335:BlogPost:1396|title=Why I Support Obama by Judy Blume - YA for Obama|date=2008-12-31|access-date=2019-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231211342/http://yaforobama.ning.com/profiles/blog/show?id=2246335:BlogPost:1396|archive-date=2008-12-31}}</ref> [[Scott Westerfeld]], [[Lauren Myracle]], [[Cecily von Ziegesar]], and [[Megan McCafferty]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://yaforobama.ning.com/profiles/blog/show?id=2246335%3ABlogPost%3A13877|title=How to Persuade Your Parents to Vote For Obama by Megan McCafferty - YA for Obama|date=2008-12-11|access-date=2019-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211214118/http://yaforobama.ning.com/profiles/blog/show?id=2246335%3ABlogPost%3A13877|archive-date=2008-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://yaforobama.ning.com/|title=YA for Obama|date=2009-04-20|access-date=2019-02-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328130900/http://yaforobama.ning.com/|archive-date=2010-03-28}}</ref>\n\n=== ShelterBox ===\nIn February 2011, in response to the [[2011 Christchurch earthquake|earthquake in Christchurch]], New Zealand, Johnson took to Twitter in an effort to raise funds for [[ShelterBox]], an international disaster relief charity established in 2000 in Helston, Cornwall, UK, that provides emergency shelter and other aid items to families around the world who have lost their homes to disaster or conflict.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/02/23/the-last-little-shelterbox/|title=Maureen Johnson Books \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb THE LAST LITTLE SHELTERBOX|date=2011-02-26|access-date=2019-09-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110226103102/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/02/23/the-last-little-shelterbox/|archive-date=2011-02-26}}</ref> A ShelterBox (the actual aid kit itself) is designed to provide families with stable, lasting shelter and a level of independence after a disaster, and include high quality aid items chosen to best suit to the particular situation at hand. As described by Johnson at the time:<blockquote>''When there\u2019s a disaster, Shelterbox deploys trained volunteers (hardcore people who\u2019ve done survival training) with their special shelters in a box. The kits vary, but all contain the basic life-sustaining materials people need to survive after a disaster. Tents that fit families of ten. Blankets. A stove. Tools. You can get a good look at the kits here. Use your mouse to examine the various contents. Each box costs \u00a3590 (about $950) and literally puts a roof over someone\u2019s head.''</blockquote>Funds were raised through a general call to action and the giving away of signed ARCs (advance reader copies of books) and other literary materials to donors. The prizes themselves were donated by various authors in support of the aid effort. Donors were asked to make contributions to the charity directly, while sharing a common label so that their total as a group could be tracked. The amount raised was $15,202 USD, enough to fund 16 shelters and supplies.\n\nWeeks later, when the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]] occurred, Johnson returned to Twitter with fellow authors to attempt to replicate the aid that was raised, this time with the people of Japan and anyone directly affected by the earthquake and tsunami in mind.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/03/11/shelterbox-in-japan/|title=Maureen Johnson Books \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb SHELTERBOX IN JAPAN|date=2011-03-15|access-date=2019-09-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315022449/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/03/11/shelterbox-in-japan/|archive-date=2011-03-15}}</ref> Almost the same amount of money was raised, totaling $14,202 USD<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/03/13/shelterbox-in-japan-the-results/|title=Maureen Johnson Books \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb SHELTERBOX IN JAPAN: THE RESULTS!|date=2012-03-20|access-date=2019-09-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320184711/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/03/13/shelterbox-in-japan-the-results/|archive-date=2012-03-20}}</ref>, enough for an additional 14 shelter kits to be deployed to those who needed them.\n\nIn May, in response to the [[2011 Joplin tornado|tornado in Joplin, Missouri]], Johnson and fellow authors used the same strategy to raise an additional $4,913.90 USD, with funds split between ShelterBox and the [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/05/23/shelter-for-joplin/|title=Maureen Johnson Books \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb SHELTER FOR JOPLIN|date=2013-05-14|access-date=2019-09-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514021753/http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com/2011/05/23/shelter-for-joplin/|archive-date=2013-05-14}}</ref>\n\nJohnson has continued to advocate publicly via social media for awareness on behalf of ShelterBox at times of disaster and particular need.\n\n== Other creative projects ==\n\n=== VlogBrothers ===\nIn January 2010, Johnson was acknowledged as [[John Green (author)|John Green]]'s ''secret sister'' on the popular [[YouTube]] channel [[Vlogbrothers|VlogBrothers]]. With the reveal of this honorary title, Johnson took on the role of creating videos for the channel during his absence to paternity leave. Johnson later reprised the duty after the birth of Green's second child in 2013.\n\n=== Welcome to Night Vale ===\nSince June 2014, Johnson has voiced the character Intern Maureen on the surreal fiction podcast ''[[Welcome to Night Vale]]'', as well as occasionally performed the character live on stage. In June 2016, while in conversation at [[92nd Street Y|92Y]] in New York, co-creator Joseph Fink explained that the character of Intern Maureen was initially written in the image of Johnson, but quickly killed off, as death is a kind of tradition for most interns of the Night Vale Radio station. Johnson, a vocal fan<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/368933183032528896|title=Now that I've found @NightValeRadio, I don't need superfluities, like scuba, or wifi, or food, or clothes. Night Vale takes care of me.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2013-08-17|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-08-13}}</ref> of the podcast, in turn led a Twitter campaign in protest, leading Fink and Cranor to agree to bring the character back on the condition that Johnson perform the role herself. Intern Maureen's continued survival has since become an ongoing joke within the stories. Johnson provided the foreword for ''The Great Glowing Coils of the Universe'' (Harper Perennial, 2016), a collected volume of early podcast scripts.\n\n=== Says Who? ===\nIn September 2016, Johnson began co-hosting the podcast ''[http://www.sayswhopodcast.com Says Who?]'' alongside former [[Punk Planet]] editor and author Dan Sinker. Self-described as a coping strategy, ''Says Who?'' was originally conceived as an eight-week project in which Johnson and Sinker would talk with political experts about how they were surviving news coverage of the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 Presidential Election]]. The podcast has since continued past the results of the election, and switched to a biweekly format in which the hosts attempt to humorously discuss the news of the day, and more personally, share how they are coping as citizens in the current political era.\n\n==Personal life==\nJohnson lives in New York City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/1023306629058637825|title=I have lived in NYC since 1997!|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2018-07-28|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> A self-described [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]] since 1994, she has frequently shared her love for both vegan and vegetarian cooking through blog posts and tweets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/38423732288491520|title=\"@sundust When did you become a vegetarian, and why?\" In 1994, and FOR MANY REASONS.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2011-02-17|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> \"I'm a vegetarian from Philadelphia, which means I spend my life trying to make a vegetarian steak sandwich.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/1023306178967887877|title=I'm a vegetarian from Philadelphia, which means I spend my life trying to make a vegetarian steak sandwich.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2018-07-28|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nOn June 23, 2018, Johnson was married in New York's [[Central Park]] at the [[The Ramble and Lake|Ladies Pavilion]]. The reception was held shortly thereafter at [[Housing Works]], a non-profit bookstore and venue space whose mission is to end the dual crises of [[homelessness]] and [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/1011314860884418562|title=So when I get the photos I hope to take you on a tour of this MAGICAL OCCASION which was really just perfect. We were married in Central Park, at the Ladies Pavilion, surrounded by friends and family. Then we took off and walked ALL THROUGH THE PARK.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2018-06-25|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> Reflecting upon the experience on Twitter, she wrote \"There was no better place to have a party on Pride weekend.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maureenjohnson/status/1011315147191746564?s=20|title=Thank you to so many people for making it all happen. Thank you to @HousingWorksBks. There was no better place to have a party on Pride weekend. Thank you to @DaphneUn and @herzwesten. And thank YOU, dear Reader.|last=Johnson|first=Maureen|date=2018-06-25|website=@maureenjohnson|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Standalone novels===\n\n*''[[The Key to the Golden Firebird|The Key to the Golden Firebird]]'' (May 25, 2004)\n*''The Bermudez Triangle'' (October 7, 2004), later reissued in America as ''On the Count of Three'' (April 18, 2013)\n*''Devilish'' (September 7, 2006)\n*''Girl at Sea'' (May 29, 2007)\n*''[[Let It Snow: Three Holiday Romances|Let It Snow: Three Holiday Romances]]'' (Co-written with [[John Green (author)|John Green]] and [[Lauren Myracle]]) (October 2, 2008)\n\n===Series novels===\n\n====13 Little Blue Envelopes====\n\n*''[[13 Little Blue Envelopes|13 Little Blue Envelopes]]'' (August 23, 2005)\n*''The Last Little Blue Envelope'' (April 26, 2011)\n\n====Suite Scarlett====\n\n*''Suite Scarlett'' (May 1, 2008)\n*''Scarlett Fever'' (February 1, 2010)\n\n====Shades of London====\n\n*''The Name of the Star'' (September 29, 2011)\n*''The Madness Underneath'' (February 26, 2013)\n* ''The Boy in the Smoke ''(Prequel novella for World Book Day) (February 24, 2014)\n* ''The Shadow Cabinet'' (February 10, 2015)\n\n====Truly Devious====\n\n*''Truly Devious'' (January 16, 2018)\n*''The Vanishing Stair'' (January 22, 2019)\n*''The Hand on the Wall'' (January 21, 2020)\n\n===Anthologized novellas===\n\n==== The Bane Chronicles ====\nCo-written with [[Cassandra Clare]] & [[Sarah Rees Brennan]] \n*''The Runaway Queen'' (May 21, 2013)\n*''The Rise of the Hotel Dumort'' (August 20, 2013)\n*''The Fall of the Hotel Dumort'' (October 15, 2013)\n*''The Last Stand of the New York Institute'' (December 17, 2013)\n*''The Bane Chronicles'' (Compiled print edition - November 11, 2014)\n\n====Tales from the Shadowhunter Academy====\nCo-written with [[Cassandra Clare]], [[Sarah Rees Brennan]] & [[Robin Wasserman]] \n*''The Whitechapel Fiend'' (April 21, 2015)\n*''The Fiery Trial'' (September 22, 2015)\n*''Tales from the Shadowhunter Academy'' (Compiled print edition - November 15, 2016)\n\n====Ghosts of the Shadow Market: An Anthology of Tales====\nCo-written with [[Cassandra Clare]], [[Sarah Rees Brennan]], [[Kelly Link]] & [[Robin Wasserman]]\n\n*''Every Exquisite Thing'' (June 12, 2018)\n*''A Deeper Love'' (August 14, 2018)\n*''Ghosts of the Shadow Market: An Anthology of Tales'' (Compiled print edition - June 4, 2019)\n\n===Other publications===\n==== Anthologies edited ====\n* ''How I Resist: Activism and Hope for a New Generation'' (May 15, 2018)\n\n==== Short stories ====\n*\"The Law of Suspects\" in ''Vacations From Hell'' (May 26, 2009)\n*\"The Children of the Revolution\" in ''Zombies vs. Unicorns'' (September 21, 2010)\n\n====Essays====\n*\"Hot Sex and Horrific Parenting in His Dark Materials\" in ''The World of the Golden Compass'' (January 28, 2007)\n*\"Stupid Monsters and Child Surgeons\" in ''Life Inside My Mind: 31 Authors Share Their Personal Struggles'' (April 10, 2018)\n\n==== Short works in support of the Harry Potter Alliance (e-book only) ====\n\n* \"1776: A Story in Tweets\" first released to donors of the HPA's Equality FTW campaign (September 9, 2012)\n* \"A Study in Sink\" first released to donors of the HPA's Equality FTW 2013 campaign (February 11, 2014)\n* \"The Sign of Tree\" first released to donors of the HPA's Equality FTW 2014 campaign (February 20, 2015)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n*<big>''13 Little Blue Envelopes'' - [[American Library Association|ALA]] Teens' Top Ten 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/ala/yalsa/teenreading/teenstopten/06ttt.cfm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-05-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080525131847/http://www.ala.org/ala/yalsa/teenreading/teenstopten/06ttt.cfm |archivedate=2008-05-25 }}</ref></big>\n*<big>''Devilish'' - 2007 [[Andre Norton Award]] nomination<ref>http://www.sfawardswatch.com/?page_id=72</ref></big>\n*<big>\"Most Interesting Twitter User to Follow\" [[Mashable]] Open Web Awards 2009<ref>http://mashable.com/2009/12/16/open-web-awards-2009-50-winners/</ref></big>\n*<big>Ranked as number 15 of TIME's \"The 140 Best Twitter Feeds of 2011\"</big><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2058946_2060626,00.html|title=The 140 Best Twitter Feeds of 2011 - TIME|date=2011-03-28|work=Time|access-date=2019-09-15|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref>\n*<big>''The Name of the Star'' - [[YALSA]] 2012 Best Fiction for Young Adults<ref>http://www.ala.org/yalsa/bfya/2012</ref></big>\n*<big>''The Name of the Star'' - [[Edgar Award]] nomination for excellence in [[Young adult fiction|Young Adult fiction]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theedgars.com/nominees.html|title=Edgar Nominees|date=2012-03-07|access-date=2019-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307172053/http://www.theedgars.com/nominees.html|archive-date=2012-03-07}}</ref></big>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Maureen Johnson}}\n*{{official website|http://www.maureenjohnsonbooks.com}}\n*[https://lccn.loc.gov/n2003054816 Maureen Johnson] at [[Library of Congress]] Authorities\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080622121816/http://www.thisispoint.com/authors/maureenjohnson.asp Scholastic Point author bio]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Maureen}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:American young adult novelists]]\n[[Category:Columbia University School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:University of Delaware alumni]]\n[[Category:Women writers of young adult literature]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American women podcasters]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:Internet activists]]\n", "name_user": "Seanfrosting", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected nationality and work focus in the short description tag.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maureen_Johnson"}
